hild Killer]]\n* [[Saginaw Trail]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite book |first= Samuel W. |last= Durant |url= https://archive.org/details/afk0725.0001.001.umich.edu |title= History of Oakland County, Michigan: With Illustrations Descriptive of Its Scenery, Palatial Residences, Public Buildings, Fine Blocks, and Important Manufactories, From Original Sketches by Artists of the Highest Ability |location= Philadelphia |publisher= L.H. Everts and Co.|year= 1877}}\n*{{cite book |first1=Walter |last1=Romig |title=Michigan Place Names: The History of the Founding and the Naming of More than Five Thousand Past and Present Michigan Communities |series=Great Lakes Books  |origyear= 1973 |year= 1986 |publisher=[[Wayne State University Press]] |isbn = 978-0814318386 |location=Detroit}}\n* {{cite book |first= Thaddeus DeWitt |last= Seeley |title= History of Oakland County Michigan: A Narrative Account of Its Historic Progress, Its People, and Its Principal Interests |location= Chicago |publisher= Lewis Publishing Co. |year= 1912}} [https://archive.org/details/historyoaklandc01seelgoog Volume 1]. [https://archive.org/details/historyoaklandc00seelgoog Volume 2]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.oakgov.com/ Oakland County Government official website]\n*[http://www.oakgov.com/oss/assets/docs/base_CVTs_letter.pdf Map of Oakland County]\n*[http://www.rcocweb.org/ The Road Commission for Oakland County]\n*[http://www.hti.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=micounty;cc=micounty;sid=b92ef34ac7eae292063c88e0fdcc9d82;q1=Oakland;view=toc;idno=arx1007.0001.001 ''An Account of Oakland County''] edited by Lillian Drake Avery. Dayton, Ohio: National Historical Association, Inc., [1925?]\n*{{cite web |url=http://clarke.cmich.edu/resource_tab/bibliographies_of_clarke_library_material/michigan_local_history/county_material/oakland.html |publisher=[[Clarke Historical Library]], [[Central Michigan University]] |title=Bibliography on Oakland County|accessdate=January 29, 2013}}\n*[http://www.automationalley.com Automation Alley]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Oakland County, Michigan\n|Northwest = [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]]\n|North     = [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]]<br />[[Lapeer County, Michigan|Lapeer County]]\n|Northeast = [[Lapeer County, Michigan|Lapeer County]]\n|East      = [[Macomb County, Michigan|Macomb County]]\n|Southeast = [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County (Detroit)]]\n|South = [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]]\n|Southwest = [[Washtenaw County, Michigan|Washtenaw County]]\n|West      = [[Livingston County, Michigan|Livingston County]]\n}}\n\n{{Oakland County, Michigan}}\n{{Metro Detroit}}\n{{Michigan}}\n\n{{Coord|42.66|-83.38|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-MI_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Michigan counties]]\n[[Category:Oakland County, Michigan| ]]\n[[Category:Metro Detroit]]\n[[Category:1820 establishments in Michigan Territory]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1820]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Oakland County\n| state = Michigan\n|type=[[County (United States)|County]]\n|official_name=County of Oakland\n| ex image = Pontiac Commercial Historic District B.JPG\n| ex image size = 250px\n| ex image cap = [[Pontiac Commercial Historic District]]\n| seal = Seal of Oakland County, Michigan.svg\n| founded year = 1819 (created)<br/>1820 (organized)<ref name=\"Clarke\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cmich.edu/library/clarke/AccessMaterials/Bibliographies/MichiganLocalHistory/Pages/oakland.aspx|publisher=[[Clarke Historical Library]], [[Central Michigan University]]|title=Bibliography on Oakland County|accessdate=January 29, 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006084440/https://www.cmich.edu/library/clarke/AccessMaterials/Bibliographies/MichiganLocalHistory/Pages/oakland.aspx|archivedate=October 6, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>[http://oaklandweb.com/govt/county/county_history.htm \"History of Oakland County,\" ''OaklandWeb.com''.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060705102642/http://oaklandweb.com/govt/county/county_history.htm |date=July 5, 2006 }} Retrieved February 7, 2007.</ref>\n| founded date = January 12\n| seat wl = Pontiac\n| largest city wl = Troy\n| area_total_sq_mi = 907\n| area_land_sq_mi = 868\n| area_water_sq_mi = 40\n| area percentage = 4.4%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop = 1,259,201\n| density_sq_mi = 1386\n| time zone = Eastern\n| web = www.oakgov.com\n| district = 8th\n| district2 = 9th\n| district3 = 11th\n| district4 = 14th\n}}\n\n'''Oakland County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. It is part of the [[Metro Detroit|metropolitan Detroit]] area, located northwest of the city. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], its population was 1,202,362,<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/26/26125.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=August 29, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714193415/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/26/26125.html|archivedate=July 14, 2011|df=mdy-all}}</ref> making it the second-most populous county in Michigan, behind neighboring [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]]. The [[county seat]] is [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=May 31, 2011 }}</ref> The county was founded in 1819 and organized in 1820.<ref name=\"Clarke\"/><ref>{{cite book|title=History of Oakland County, Michigan|publisher=L. H. Everts and Co.|place=Philadelphia|date=1877|page=[https://archive.org/details/afk0725.0001.001.umich.edu/page/23 23]|url=https://archive.org/details/afk0725.0001.001.umich.edu|accessdate=October 4, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120214645/https://archive.org/details/afk0725.0001.001.umich.edu|archivedate=November 20, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOakland County is composed of 62 cities, townships, and villages, and is part of the [[Detroit]]-[[Warren, Michigan|Warren]]-[[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]], MI [[Metro Detroit|Metropolitan Statistical Area]]. The city of Detroit is in neighboring [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]], south of [[M-102 (Michigan highway)|8 Mile Road]]. Oakland County is among the ten highest income counties in the United States with populations over one million people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.detroitchamber.com/region/About-Detroit/Quick-Facts/925-population|title=Detroit Regional Chamber of Commerce - quick facts|website=detroitchamber.com|accessdate=April 29, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121010002152/http://www.detroitchamber.com/region/About-Detroit/Quick-Facts/925-population|archivedate=October 10, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> It is also home to [[Oakland University]], a large public institution that straddles the [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]] and [[Rochester Hills, Michigan|Rochester Hills]] border.\n\nThe county's knowledge-based economic initiative, coined \"Automation Alley\", has developed one of the largest employment centers for engineering and related occupations in the United States, and some major employers include [[General Motors Corporation|General Motors]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], and [[Chrysler]], collectively known as the [[Big Three (automobile manufacturers)|Big Three]]. \n==History==\n{{See also|List of National Historic Landmarks in Michigan|National Register of Historic Places listings in Oakland County, Michigan}}\n\nFounded by Territorial Governor [[Lewis Cass]] in 1819, sparsely settled Oakland was originally twice its current size. As was customary at the time, as populations increased, other counties were organized from its land area. Woodward Avenue and the [[Detroit and Pontiac Railroad]] helped draw settlers in the 1840s. By 1840, Oakland had more than fifty lumber mills, processing wood harvested from the region and the Upper Peninsula. Pontiac, located on the [[Clinton River (Michigan)|Clinton River]], was Oakland's first town and became the county seat. After the Civil War, Oakland was still primarily a rural, agricultural county with numerous isolated villages. By the end of the 19th century, three rail lines served Pontiac, and the city attracted carriage and wagon factories. In the late 1890s streetcars were constructed here and to Detroit.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nAt that time, developers made southern Oakland County a suburb of Detroit; a Cincinnati firm platted a section of Royal Oak called \"Urbanrest.\" Migration worked both ways. Several thousand people moved from Oakland County farms to Detroit as the city attracted factories. By 1910, a number of rich [[Detroit]]ers had summer homes and some year-round residences in what became Bloomfield Hills. The auto age enveloped Pontiac in the early 1900s. The [[Oakland (automobile)|Oakland Motor Car Company]] was founded in 1907 and became a part of General Motors Corp., which was soon Pontiac's dominant firm.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nIn the 1950s, the Detroit metropolitan population began migrating to the suburbs, aided by the GI Bill for veterans and federal subsidies for highways and freeways.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} Oakland County is among the ten highest-income counties in the United States with more than one million population.{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} The median price of a home in Oakland County increased to $164,697, more than $30,000 above the national median. Oakland County is home to popular super-regional shopping malls such as [[Somerset Collection]], [[Twelve Oaks Mall]], and [[Great Lakes Crossing Outlets]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}}\n\nOn March 10, 2020, Michigan reported the first 2 coronavirus cases, one of which was in Oakland County.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|907|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|868|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|40|sqmi}} (4.4%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_26.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 27, 2014|date=August 22, 2012|title=2010 Census Gazetteer Files|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113024015/http://www.census.gov/geo/maps-data/data/docs/gazetteer/counties_list_26.txt|archivedate=November 13, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nOakland County was originally divided into 25 separate [[townships]], which are listed below. Each township is roughly equal in size at six miles (10&nbsp;km) by six miles, for a total township area of {{convert|36|sqmi|km2}}.  The roots of this design were born out of the [[Land Ordinance of 1785]] and the subsequent [[Northwest Ordinance]] of 1787.  Oakland County itself is a prime example of the land policy that was established, as all townships are equal in size (save for slight variations due to waterways).  Section 16 in each township was reserved for financing and maintaining public education, and even today many schools in Oakland County townships are located within that section.\n\n[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]], where the city of [[Detroit, Michigan|Detroit]] is located, borders Oakland County to the south. [[8 Mile Road]], also known as \"Baseline Road\" in some areas, is the boundary between these counties.  The baseline was used during the original surveying for Michigan, and it serves as the northern/southern boundaries for counties from [[Lake Saint Clair (North America)|Lake St. Clair]] to [[Lake Michigan]]. As more working and middle-class populations moved to the suburbs from the 1950s on, this divide (8 Mile Road) became historically known as an unofficial racial dividing line between what became the predominantly [[Black people|black]] city and almost exclusively [[whites|white]] suburbs.\n\nSince the late 20th century, however, the patterns of ''de facto'' [[Racial segregation|segregation]] have faded as the suburbs have become more diverse. Middle-class African Americans have left the city, settling in inner-ring suburbs, notably Southfield (75.08%), west of [[M-1 (Michigan highway)|Woodward Avenue]]. Based on the 2010 Census, the following cities also have significant minority ethnic populations: Farmington (25.3%), Farmington Hills (31.7%), Novi (30.12%), [[Oak Park, Michigan|Oak Park]] (62.61%), Lathrup Village (72.97%), Orchard Lake Village (16.08%), Rochester Hills (20.94%), Troy (29.4%), Wixom (26.28%), West Bloomfield (24.0%), Bloomfield (18.28%), Bloomfield Hills (14.2%), [[Ferndale, Michigan|Ferndale]] (17.2%), and Madison Heights (17.7%). Ferndale has a concentration of [[Arab Americans]], who also live in nearby areas, and numerous [[Asian Americans]], particularly [[India]]ns, have also settled in these areas.\n\n===Adjacent counties===\n*[[Lapeer County, Michigan|Lapeer County]] (northeast)\n*[[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]] (northwest)\n*[[Macomb County, Michigan|Macomb County]] (east)\n*[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]] (southeast)\n*[[Washtenaw County, Michigan|Washtenaw County]] (southwest)\n*[[Livingston County, Michigan|Livingston County]] (west)\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1820= 330\n|1830= 4911\n|1840= 23646\n|1850= 31270\n|1860= 38261\n|1870= 40867\n|1880= 41537\n|1890= 41245\n|1900= 44792\n|1910= 49576\n|1920= 90050\n|1930= 211251\n|1940= 254068\n|1950= 396001\n|1960= 690259\n|1970= 907871\n|1980= 1011793\n|1990= 1083592\n|2000= 1194156\n|2010= 1202362\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=1259201\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{citeweb|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml|title=QuickFacts|accessdate=April 18, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717015826/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/16/16055.html|archive-date=July 17, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 27, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=September 27, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120811110448/http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu/|archivedate=August 11, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/mi190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 27, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215142038/http://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/mi190090.txt|archivedate=February 15, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=September 27, 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218203824/http://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|archivedate=December 18, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> 2010-2018<ref name=\"QF\"/>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]], there were 1,202,362 people and 315,175 families residing in the county. 77.3% were [[White American|White]], 13.6% [[African American|Black or African American]], 5.6% [[Asian American|Asian]], 0.3% [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], 1.0% of some other race and 2.2% [[Multiracial American|of two or more races]]. 3.5% were [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race). There were 527,255 housing units at an average density of 564 per square mile (218/km\u00b2).<ref name=\"U.S. Census State and County Quick Facts\">{{cite web |url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/26/26125.html |title=Oakland County QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau |url-status=dead |accessdate=July 6, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714193415/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/26/26125.html |archivedate=July 14, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nRegarding ancestry, in 2000 14.4% of the population were ethnically [[Germans|German]], 9.0% [[Irish people|Irish]], 8.5% [[English people|English]], 8.5% [[poles|Polish]], 5.7% [[Italians|Italian]] and 5.5% [[United States|American]], 87.4% spoke only [[English language|English]] at home; 2.0% spoke [[Spanish language|Spanish]], 1.3% [[Syriac language|Syriac (Neo Aramaic)]] and 1.0% [[Arabic language|Arabic]].  The [[population density]] as of the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]] was 1,369 people per square mile (528/km\u00b2). There were 492,006 housing units at an average density of 564 per square mile (218/km\u00b2).\n\nThe 2000 census showed two Native American tribes with more than 1,000 members in Oakland County.  There were 2,095 Cherokee and 1,458 Chippewa.\n\nThe Jewish community of metropolitan Detroit, with a population of 72,000, is the 21st largest Jewish community in the nation.  This community is concentrated in Oakland County, especially in West Bloomfield, Bloomfield Hills, Farmington Hills, Troy and Huntington Woods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://detroitjcrc.org/community_relations/detroit.php?page=10080 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-08-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725231357/http://detroitjcrc.org/community_relations/detroit.php?page=10080 |archivedate=July 25, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThere were 471,115 households, of which 32.40% had children under the age of 18 living with them.  54.20% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 9.50% had a female householder with no husband present, and 33.10% were non-families. 27.30% of all households were made up of individuals and 8.50% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.51 and the average family size was 3.09.\n\nAmong Asian Americans, eight ethnic groups had more than 1,000 members in the county in 2000. The most numerous were those of [[Indian American|Asian Indian]] descent, with 20,705. Next were those of [[Chinese American|Chinese]] heritage, numbering 10,018. Next were those of [[Japanese American|Japanese]] (5,589), [[Filipino American|Filipino]] (5,450) [[Korean American|Korean]] (5,351), [[Vietnamese American|Vietnamese]] (1,687), [[Pakistani American|Pakistani]] (1,458) and [[Hmong people|Hmong]] (1,210) ancestry.<ref name=\"search results\">See [http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-context=dt&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-CONTEXT=dt&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT007&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT010&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT011&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT003&-tree_id=4001&-redoLog=true&-all_geo_types=N&-_caller=geoselect&-geo_id=05000US26099&-geo_id=05000US26125&-geo_id=05000US26127&-geo_id=05000US26163&-search_results=01000US&-format=&-_lang=en search results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608174512/http://factfinder.census.gov/servlet/DTTable?_bm=y&-context=dt&-ds_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U&-CONTEXT=dt&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT007&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT010&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT011&-mt_name=DEC_2000_SF1_U_PCT003&-tree_id=4001&-redoLog=true&-all_geo_types=N&-_caller=geoselect&-geo_id=05000US26099&-geo_id=05000US26125&-geo_id=05000US26127&-geo_id=05000US26163&-search_results=01000US&-format=&-_lang=en |date=June 8, 2011 }} from ''[[United States Census Bureau]]''. Retrieved July 2, 2007.</ref>\n\nIn 2001, Oakland County had the 36th largest Asian population of any county in the country.<ref>Metzger, Kurt and Jason Booza. \"[http://www.cus.wayne.edu/content/publications/Asians7.pdf Asians in the United States, Michigan and Metropolitan Detroit] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109050601/http://www.cus.wayne.edu/content/publications/Asians7.pdf |date=November 9, 2013 }}.\" [[Wayne State University]] Center for Urban Studies-January 2001 Working Paper Series, No. 7, p. 5. Retrieved on September 8, 2013.</ref> In 2002, of the Oakland-[[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne]]-[[Macomb County, Michigan|Macomb]] tricounty area, Oakland County had 49% of the tri-county area's Asian population.<ref>Metzger, Kurt and Jason Booza. \"[http://www.cus.wayne.edu/content/publications/Asians7.pdf Asians in the United States, Michigan and Metropolitan Detroit] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109050601/http://www.cus.wayne.edu/content/publications/Asians7.pdf |date=November 9, 2013 }}.\" Center for Urban Studies, [[Wayne State University]]. January 2002 Working Paper Series, No. 7. p. 7. Retrieved on November 6, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe county's population was spread out in terms of age, with 25.20% of people under the age of 18, 7.20% from 18 to 24, 32.40% from 25 to 44, 23.90% from 45 to 64, and 11.30% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 37 years. For every 100 females, there were 95.90 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 92.70 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $86,567, making Oakland County the 21st wealthiest county in the United States: (http://www.worldatlas.com/articles/richest-counties-in-the-united-states.html). Males had a median income of $55,833 versus $35,890 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $65,759. About 3.80% of families and 5.50% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.50% of those under age 18 and 6.50% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government==\n{{More citations needed section|date=February 2012}}\n\nThe county government operates the [[County jail|jail]], operates the major local courts, keeps files of deeds and mortgages, maintains [[vital records]], administers [[public health]] regulations, and participates with the state in the provision of welfare and other social services. The [[county commission|county board of commissioners]] controls the budget but has limited authority to make laws or ordinances. In Michigan, most local government functions&mdash;police and fire, building and zoning, tax assessment, street maintenance, etc. &mdash; are the responsibility of individual cities and townships. Oakland County has an elected sheriff, and his or her law-enforcement services are used throughout the county. Fourteen cities/townships do not have municipal police forces, but rather contract with the sheriff for police services specific to the municipalities. For instance, the city of Rochester Hills does not have a \"Rochester Hills Police Department,\" but instead has an established sheriff substation in the city with deputies who are dedicated to that city only. That branch operates as the Oakland County Sheriff's Department, Rochester Hills substation. The sheriff operates in the same manner with other municipalities who opt not to have their own police agencies. This typically is a cost-effective way for municipalities to provide police services to its citizens.  The county sheriff also maintains a civil division, marine division, alcohol and traffic enforcement units, and an aviation division.\n\n===Elected officials===\n* [[County Executive]]: [[David Coulter (politician)|Dave Coulter]] (Democrat){{ref|a}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/03/l-brooks-patterson-oakland-county-gerald-poisson/1909186001/|title=L. Brooks Patterson's successor as Oakland County executive|first=Bill|last=Laitner|website=Detroit Free Press}}</ref>\n* [[Prosecutor|Prosecuting Attorney]]: [[Jessica R. Cooper]] (Democrat)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.detnews.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090115/METRO/901150398|title=New Oakland prosecutor 'going pretty hard'|last=Martindale|first=Mike|date=January 15, 2009|newspaper=The Detroit News|accessdate=March 1, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Sheriff]]: [[Mike Bouchard]] (Republican)\n* [[County Clerk]]/[[Register of Deeds]]: [[Lisa Brown (Michigan politician)|Lisa Brown]] (Democrat)\n* [[Treasurer|County Treasurer]]: [[Andy Meisner]] (Democrat)\n* [[Water Resources Commissioner]]: [[James H. Nash|Jim Nash]] (Democrat)\n* [[County Commission|Board of Commissioners]]: 21 members, elected from districts (11 Democrats, 10 Republicans)\n\n<small>(information as of August 4, 2019)</small>\n\n===Road Commission===\nRoads that are not maintained by a local community (city/village) are maintained by the independent Road Commission for Oakland County, which is governed by three board members appointed by the Oakland County Board of Commissioners.\nRoad Commissioners:  Eric. S. Wilson, Chairman; Gregory C. Jamian Vice Chairman; Ron Fowkes\nDennis G. Kolar, Managing Director\n\n===Oakland County Service Center===\nThe East Campus of the Oakland County Service Center is located in [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]]. It includes the county courthouse and jail for adults.<ref name=Complexmap>\"[https://www.oakgov.com/maps/Documents/occomplexmap.pdf Complex Map]\" ({{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710032719/https://www.oakgov.com/maps/Documents/occomplexmap.pdf |date=2015-07-10 }}). Oakland County Government. Retrieved on July 9, 2015.</ref>\n\nThe West Campus of the Oakland County Service Center is located in [[Waterford Township, Michigan|Waterford Township]].<ref name=Complexmap/><ref>\"[http://twp.waterford.mi.us/Departments/GIS-and-Online-Mapping/Documents/Generic-Base-Map-2014.aspx Generic Base Map 2014]\" ({{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113150851/http://twp.waterford.mi.us/Departments/GIS-and-Online-Mapping/Documents/Generic-Base-Map-2014.aspx |date=2015-01-13 }}). [[Waterford Township, Michigan|Waterford Township]]. Retrieved on July 10, 2015.</ref> This includes the Oakland County Executive Building and Conference Center,<ref>\"[https://www.oakgov.com/advantageoakland/media-center/Documents/Maps/map_eob.pdf Oakland County Executive Office Building Conference Center Locator Map & Directions]\" ({{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710114738/https://www.oakgov.com/advantageoakland/media-center/Documents/Maps/map_eob.pdf |date=2015-07-10 }}). Oakland County Government. Retrieved on July 10, 2015.</ref> and the Oakland County Children's Village,<ref name=Complexmap/> the county's [[juvenile detention center]] for children.<ref>\"[https://www.oakgov.com/village Oakland County Children's Village]\" ({{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710014343/https://www.oakgov.com/village |date=2015-07-10 }}). The Government of Oakland County. Retrieved on July 9, 2015. \"Oakland County Children's Village 1200 North Telegraph Road Pontiac, MI 48341\"</ref> The Children's Village acts as one of the support sites for the [[Waterford School District]].<ref>\"[http://www.waterford.k12.mi.us/NorthstarMedia/download/97671?token=OCaRojCyVwc%3d District Map]\" ( {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904112756/http://www.waterford.k12.mi.us/NorthstarMedia/download/97671?token=OCaRojCyVwc%3d |date=September 4, 2015 }}). [[Waterford School District]]. Retrieved on July 9, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nOakland County was historically a classic bastion of suburban conservatism, and was hence a longstanding stronghold of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].{{cn|date=March 2020}} However, since the 1990s it has become more competitive and has voted for the Democratic candidate for President in the last six elections.\n\nIn 1996, Bill Clinton became the first Democrat to secure the plurality of Oakland County presidential votes since Lyndon Johnson in 1964, and only the fourth to do so since 1892. Al Gore and John Kerry also carried the county, by narrow margins, against George W. Bush in 2000 and 2004, respectively. In 2008, Barack Obama became the first Democrat to win a majority in the county since Lyndon Johnson in 1964. (''See table at right''.) He again carried the county in 2012, though by a smaller margin.\n\nWhile the Democratic Party has found increasing success in Presidential elections in Oakland County, the state Republican Party has remained strong in recent gubernatorial and state elections. The county favored Governor [[Rick Snyder]] (R) by a 22-percent margin in the [http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/MI/Oakland/22923/42960/en/summary.html 2010] statewide elections and again by a 12-point margin in [http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/MI/Oakland/54212/149511/en/summary.html 2014]. While Republicans held a majority on the County Commission for most of its history, following the 2018 elections, there are 11 Democrats and 10 Republicans.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theoaklandpress.com/news/elections/oakland-county-board-of-commissioners-majority-democratic-for-third-time/article_04063cb6-e2a4-11e8-b25c-530fb554a487.html|title=Oakland County Board of Commissioners majority Democratic for third time in history|last=Cavitt|first=Mark|date=November 7, 2018|publisher=[[The Oakland Press]]|accessdate=March 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[116th United States Congress|116th Congress]], Oakland County is represented by four Democrats, [[Brenda Lawrence]] ([[Michigan's 14th congressional district|14th]]), [[Andy Levin]] ([[Michigan's 9th congressional district|9th]]), [[Haley Stevens]] ([[Michigan's 11th congressional district|11th]]) and [[Elissa Slotkin]] ([[Michigan's 8th congressional district|8th]]). Slotkin and Stevens were first elected in 2018, flipping Republican-held seats.\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential election results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential election results'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|first=David|last=Leip|website=uselectionatlas.org|accessdate=April 29, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323225526/https://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|archivedate=March 23, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third Parties]]\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election in Michigan|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|43.2% ''289,203''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''51.3%''' ''343,070''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.5% ''36,652''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election in Michigan|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|45.4% ''296,514''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''53.4%''' ''349,002''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.2% ''8,055''\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election in Michigan|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|41.9% ''276,956''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''56.4%''' ''372,566''