ne-time assist champion, one-time Sixth Man of the Year\n* [[Lee Hsueh-Lin]] (\u674e\u5b78\u6797): 5'9\", four-time champion, one-time All-SBL Team\n\n=== Forwards ===\n* [[Chen Hsin-An]] (\u9673\u4fe1\u5b89): 6'5\", two-time champion, one-time regular season MVP, one-time finals MVP, one-time All-SBL Team, one-time scoring champion\n* [[Lin Chih-Chieh]] (\u6797\u5fd7\u5091): 6'3\", two-time champion, two-time finals MVP, one-time regular season MVP, three-time All-SBL Team, two-time scoring champion\n* [[Jonathan Sanders]] (\u6851\u5fb7\u65af): 6'7\", three-time All-SBL Team, three-time [[rebound (basketball)|rebound]] champion, two-time [[assist (basketball)|assist]] champion, one-time Fighter of the Year (\u5e74\u5ea6\u6700\u4f73\u9b25\u58eb) <ref>The SBL Fighter of the Year award is distinct from the MVP award and is not created regularly. It is a rough equivalence to a [[sportsmanship]] award and would be given to the player who has won the most Fighter of the Week awards throughout a season when a yearly award is officially created.  This has only happened in the 2003-2004 and the 2009-2010 seasons where veteran [[point guard]] Chou Chun-San (\u5468\u4fca\u4e09) and import forward Jonathan Sanders won the respective awards. The league has never explained the rationale behind its decision to create the Fighter of the Year award in certain seasons but not the others.</ref>\n* [[Tien Lei]] (\u7530\u58d8): 6'8\", one-time champion, three-time regular season MVP, three-time All-SBL Team, three-time rebound champion, two-time scoring champion, one-time [[steal (basketball)|steal]] champion\n* [[Noel Felix]]\n* [[Marcus Fizer]]\n* [[Taylor King]], Former McDonald's All-American and Duke basketball player\n\n=== Centers ===\n* [[Tseng Wen-Ting]] (\u66fe\u6587\u9f0e): 6'9\", four-time champion, two-time finals MVP, one-time regular season MVP, four-time All-SBL Team and Defensive Player of the Year, six-time [[block (basketball)|block]] champion\n* [[Wu Tai-Hao]] (\u5433\u5cb1\u8c6a): 6'8\", one-time champion, one-time All-SBL Team, one-time block champion\n* [[Patrick O'Bryant]]\n* [[Solomon Alabi]]\n* [[Garret Siler]]\n* [[Earl Barron]]\n\n== Women's Super Basketball League ==\n{{Main|Women's Super Basketball League}}\n\nThere is also a [[Women's Super Basketball League]] (WSBL) in [[Taiwan]], which comprises the following four teams:\n\n* [[Cathay Life]] (\u570b\u6cf0\u4eba\u58fd)\n* [[Chunghwa Telecom (basketball)|Chunghwa Telecom]] (\u4e2d\u83ef\u96fb\u4fe1)\n* [[Taiwan Power (basketball)|Taiwan Power]] (\u53f0\u7063\u96fb\u529b)\n* [[Taiyuan Textile]] (\u53f0\u5143\u7d21\u7e54)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[A-League (basketball)|A-League]] (second tier)\n* [[Chinese Basketball Alliance]] (CBA)\n* [[Sports in Taiwan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20121210062457/http://sports.yam.com/special/sbl/ SBL official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070603213726/http://sbl.mytaiwanbeer.com.tw/ Taiwan Beer official website]\n* [http://www.taiwanbasketball.com/ Taiwan Mobile Clouded Leopards official website]\n* [https://archive.is/20130113232824/http://www.yulon.com.tw/ Yulon Luxgen Dinos official website]\n* [http://www1.ymy.com.tw/ch2/basketball/index.htm YMY official website]\n* [http://twhoops.blogspot.com/ Taiwan Hoops]\n* [http://www.asia-basket.com/tai/d1.asp Asia-Basket - Taiwan]\n* [http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1784&Itemid=157: High flying hoop dreams: A brief history of the development of basketball in Taiwan] (in [[English language|English]])\n\n{{Men's professional basketball leagues}}\n{{SBL}}\n{{Sport in Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Super Basketball League| ]]\n[[Category:Basketball leagues in Asia|Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Basketball leagues in Taiwan|   ]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the semi-professional men's and women's basketball leagues in [[Western Australia]]|State Basketball League}}\n\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title          = Super Basketball League (SBL)\n| current_season = 2018\u201319 SBL season\n| logo           = \n| pixels         = 250px\n| caption        = Logo SBL\n| sport          = [[Basketball]]\n| founded        = 2003\n| folded         = \n| ceo            = \n| fame           = \n| motto          = \n| teams          = [[#Current clubs|5]]\n| levels         = 1\n| country        = {{ROC}}\n| continent      = [[FIBA Asia]] ([[Asia]])\n| champion       = [[Taipei Fubon Braves|Fubon Braves]] (1st title)\n| most_champs    = [[Taoyuan Pauian Archiland Basketball Team|Taoyuan Pauian Archiland]] (5 titles)\n| singles        = \n| TV             = \n| website        = [http://sbl.choxue.com/ SBL] {{in lang|zh}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Super Basketball League''' ({{zh|t=\u8d85\u7d1a\u7c43\u7403\u806f\u8cfd|s=\u8d85\u7ea7\u7bee\u7403\u8054\u8d5b|p=Ch\u0101oj\u00ed l\u00e1nqi\u00fa li\u00e1ns\u00e0i}}), often abbreviated to the '''SBL''', is the first tier semi-professional men's [[basketball]] [[list of basketball leagues|league]] in [[Taiwan]]. It was founded in 2003 and considered by many as the successor organization to the short-lived [[Chinese Basketball Alliance]] ({{zh|t=\u4e2d\u83ef\u8077\u696d\u7c43\u7403\u806f\u76df|s=\u4e2d\u534e\u804c\u4e1a\u7bee\u7403\u8054\u76df|p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 zh\u00edy\u00e8 l\u00e1nqi\u00fa li\u00e1nm\u00e9ng}}; '''CBA'''), a men's professional basketball league that existed from 1994 to 1999 in [[Taiwan]].\n\n== Current clubs ==\nCurrently, there are five teams competing in the SBL. They are as follows:\n\n* [[Bank of Taiwan (basketball)|Bank of Taiwan]] (\u81fa\u7063\u9280\u884c)\n* [[Kaohsiung Jeoutai Technology Basketball Team|Kaohsiung Jeoutai Technology]] (\u9ad8\u96c4\u4e5d\u592a\u79d1\u6280)\n* [[Taoyuan Pauian Archiland Basketball Team|Taoyuan Pauian Archiland]] (\u6843\u5712\u749e\u5712\u5efa\u7bc9)\n* [[Taiwan Beer (basketball)|Taiwan Beer]] (\u53f0\u7063\u5564\u9152)\n* [[Yulon Luxgen Dinos]] (\u88d5\u9686\u7d0d\u667a\u6377)\n\n=== Former and defunct clubs ===\n* [[Dacin Tigers]] (\u9054\u6b23\u5de5\u7a0b) \u2013 now defunct\n* [[Taipei Fubon Braves]] (\u81fa\u5317\u5bcc\u90a6\u52c7\u58eb) \u2013 now competes in the [[ASEAN Basketball League]] (ABL)\n\n== Champions ==\nChampions and other postseason finishes are listed below:\n\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=1 bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"|Season\n!colspan=1 bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"|Champions\n!colspan=1 bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"|Runners-up\n!colspan=1 bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"|Third Place\n!colspan=1 bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"|Fourth Place\n|-\n|2003\u20132004\t\n|Yulon Dinos\n|Sina Lions<ref>The Sina Lions are the precursor organization to the Taoyuan Pauian Archiland.</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|2004\u20132005\n|Yulon Dinos\n|Dacin Tigers\n|\n|\n|-\n|2005\u20132006\n|Yulon Dinos\n|Taiwan Beer\n|Dacin Tigers\n|Bank of Taiwan\n|-\n|2006\u20132007\n|Taiwan Beer\n|Dacin Tigers\n|Videoland Hunters<ref>The Videoland Hunters are the precursor organization to the Taipei Fubon Braves.</ref>\n|Yulon Dinos\n|-\n|2007\u20132008\n|Taiwan Beer\n|Yulon Dinos\n|dMedia Genies<ref>The dMedia Genies are the precursor organization to the Kaohsiung Jeoutai Technology.</ref>\n|Pauian Archiland\n|-\n|2008\u20132009\n|Dacin Tigers\n|Taiwan Beer\n|\n|\n|-\n|2009\u20132010\n|Yulon Luxgen Dinos\n|Dacin Tigers\n|\n|\n|-\n|2010\u20132011\n|Taiwan Beer\n|Dacin Tigers\n|\n|\n|-\n|2011\u20132012\n|Pauian Archiland\n|Dacin Tigers\n|\n|\n|-\n|2012\u20132013\n|Pauian Archiland\n|Dacin Tigers\n|\n|\n|-\n|2013\u20132014\n|Pauian Archiland\n|Taiwan Mobile Clouded Leopards<ref>The Taiwan Mobile Clouded Leopards are the precursor organization to the Taipei Fubon Braves.</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|2014\u20132015\n|Pauian Archiland\n|Taiwan Beer\n|\n|\n|-\n|2015\u20132016\n|Taiwan Beer\n|Pauian Archiland\n|