 All-SBL Team\n\n=== Forwards ===\n* [[Chen Hsin-An]] (\u9673\u4fe1\u5b89): 6'5\", two-time champion, one-time regular season MVP, one-time finals MVP, one-time All-SBL Team, one-time scoring champion\n* [[Lin Chih-Chieh]] (\u6797\u5fd7\u5091): 6'3\", two-time champion, two-time finals MVP, one-time regular season MVP, three-time All-SBL Team, two-time scoring champion\n* [[Jonathan Sanders]] (\u6851\u5fb7\u65af): 6'7\", three-time All-SBL Team, three-time [[rebound (basketball)|rebound]] champion, two-time [[assist (basketball)|assist]] champion, one-time Fighter of the Year (\u5e74\u5ea6\u6700\u4f73\u9b25\u58eb) <ref>The SBL Fighter of the Year award is distinct from the MVP award and is not created regularly. It is a rough equivalence to a [[sportsmanship]] award and would be given to the player who has won the most Fighter of the Week awards throughout a season when a yearly award is officially created.  This has only happened in the 2003-2004 and the 2009-2010 seasons where veteran [[point guard]] Chou Chun-San (\u5468\u4fca\u4e09) and import forward Jonathan Sanders won the respective awards. The league has never explained the rationale behind its decision to create the Fighter of the Year award in certain seasons but not the others.</ref>\n* [[Tien Lei]] (\u7530\u58d8): 6'8\", one-time champion, three-time regular season MVP, three-time All-SBL Team, three-time rebound champion, two-time scoring champion, one-time [[steal (basketball)|steal]] champion\n* [[Noel Felix]]\n* [[Marcus Fizer]]\n* [[Taylor King]], Former McDonald's All-American and Duke basketball player\n\n=== Centers ===\n* [[Tseng Wen-Ting]] (\u66fe\u6587\u9f0e): 6'9\", four-time champion, two-time finals MVP, one-time regular season MVP, four-time All-SBL Team and Defensive Player of the Year, six-time [[block (basketball)|block]] champion\n* [[Wu Tai-Hao]] (\u5433\u5cb1\u8c6a): 6'8\", one-time champion, one-time All-SBL Team, one-time block champion\n* [[Patrick O'Bryant]]\n* [[Solomon Alabi]]\n* [[Garret Siler]]\n* [[Earl Barron]]\n\n== Women's Super Basketball League ==\n{{Main|Women's Super Basketball League}}\n\nThere is also a [[Women's Super Basketball League]] (WSBL) in [[Taiwan]], which comprises the following four teams:\n\n* [[Cathay Life]] (\u570b\u6cf0\u4eba\u58fd)\n* [[Chunghwa Telecom (basketball)|Chunghwa Telecom]] (\u4e2d\u83ef\u96fb\u4fe1)\n* [[Taiwan Power (basketball)|Taiwan Power]] (\u53f0\u7063\u96fb\u529b)\n* [[Taiyuan Textile]] (\u53f0\u5143\u7d21\u7e54)\n\n== See also ==\n* [[A-League (basketball)|A-League]] (second tier)\n* [[Chinese Basketball Alliance]] (CBA)\n* [[Sports in Taiwan]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://archive.is/20121210062457/http://sports.yam.com/special/sbl/ SBL official website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070603213726/http://sbl.mytaiwanbeer.com.tw/ Taiwan Beer official website]\n* [http://www.taiwanbasketball.com/ Taiwan Mobile Clouded Leopards official website]\n* [https://archive.is/20130113232824/http://www.yulon.com.tw/ Yulon Luxgen Dinos official website]\n* [http://www1.ymy.com.tw/ch2/basketball/index.htm YMY official website]\n* [http://twhoops.blogspot.com/ Taiwan Hoops]\n* [http://www.asia-basket.com/tai/d1.asp Asia-Basket - Taiwan]\n* [http://www.culture.tw/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1784&Itemid=157: High flying hoop dreams: A brief history of the development of basketball in Taiwan] (in [[English language|English]])\n\n{{Men's professional basketball leagues}}\n{{SBL}}\n{{Sport in Taiwan}}\n\n[[Category:Super Basketball League| ]]\n[[Category:Basketball leagues in Asia|Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Basketball leagues in Taiwan|   ]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 2003]]\n", "name_user": "Xindeho", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Basketball_League"}
{"title_page": "Vice-admiral of the White", "text_new": "{{short description|Rank of the navy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of the White 1805 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of White (1805-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the White\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAW \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Vice-Admiral of the Red|Vice-Admiral of the Red]] \n| lower rank     =  [[Vice-Admiral of the Blue]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the White''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank [[Vice-admiral of the red|Vice-Admiral of the Red]] (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be ''admirals''. From 1688 to 1805, this rank was fifth in order of precedence; after 1805, it was the sixth. In 1864, it was abolished as a promotional rank (pictured opposite is the command flag for a Vice-Admiral of the White).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] as an official flag rank was formally created in 1688.<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the White was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the Red (see order of precedence below). Such senior ranks or offices generally qualify the Royal Navy officers holding them to be considered ''admirals'', a category that consists of the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%20the%20ranks%20of%20rear%20admiral%2C%20vice%20admiral%20and%20admiral%20of%20the%20fleet%20are%20sometimes%20considered%20generically%20to%20be%20admirals&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1688 to 1805 the rank of Vice-Admiral of the White was fifth in the order of precedence; after 1805 it was the sixth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Services |first1=Library |title=Information sheet no 055 Squadron colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Order of precedence Admirals of the Colour==\nThe Navy was divided into three squadrons Red, White and Blue in order of seniority. Admirals were appointed to these squadrons and therefore their rank and squadron split the seniority originally into 9 bands then later 10 with \u2018Admiral of the Fleet' as senior to all others..<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1805 to 1864.:\n\n# [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]]\n# [[Admiral of the Red|Admiral of the Red Squadron]] (rank created in 1805)\n# [[Admiral of the White|Admiral of the White Squadron]] \n# [[Admiral of the Blue|Admiral of the Blue Squadron]] \n# [[Vice-admiral of the red|Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron]] \n# '''Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron'''\n# [[Vice-Admiral of the Blue|Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-admiral of the red|Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the White|Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron]]\n# [[Rear-Admiral of the Blue|Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron]]\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1688 to 1805.:\n\n# Admiral of the Fleet, (rank created in 1688)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron'''\n# Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nAdmirals without an appointment were colloquially referred to as Yellow Admirals. Ships of the Royal Navy flew the Ensign that coincided with the squadron of their commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Former command flag 1625 to 1805==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag Vice Admiral of the White 1702 to 1805.png|Vice Admiral of the White Squadron command flag 1625 to 1805.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n# [[List of command flags of the Royal Navy]]\n\n# [[Horatio_Nelson,_1st_Viscount_Nelson]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n# Perrin, W. G. (William Gordon) (1922). \"Flags of Command: Admirals Flags\". British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device. Cambridge, England: Cambridge : The University Press.\n# Squadron Colours\" (2014), (PDF). National Museum of the Royal Navy.\n\n[[Category:Military ranks of the Royal Navy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Rank of the navy of the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Infobox military rank\n| image          = Flag Vice Admiral of the White 1805 to 1864.png\n| image_size     = 150px\n| caption        = Command Flag Vice Admiral of White (1805-1864)\n| image2         =  \n| image_size2    =  \n| caption2       =  \n| image3         =  \n| image_size3    =  \n| caption3       =  \n| name           =  Vice-Admiral of the White\n| country        = {{flagu|United Kingdom|name=United Kingdom}}\n| service branch = [[Royal Navy]] \n| abbreviation   = VAW \n| rank           =  \n| NATO rank      =  \n| Non-NATO rank  =  \n| formation      =\n| abolished      =\n| higher rank    = [[Vice-Admiral of the Red|Vice-Admiral of the Red]] \n| lower rank     =  [[Vice-Admiral of the Blue]] \n| equivalents    =  \n}}\n\nThe '''Vice-Admiral of the White''' was a senior rank of the [[Royal Navy]] of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank [[Vice-admiral of the red|Vice-Admiral of the Red]] (see order of precedence below). Royal Navy officers holding the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet are sometimes considered generically to be ''admirals''. From 1688 to 1805, this rank was fifth in order of precedence; after 1805, it was the sixth. In 1864, it was abolished as a promotional rank (pictured opposite is the command flag for a Vice-Admiral of the White).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Navy Royal]] inaugurated squadron colours during the reign of Elizabeth I (1558-1603) to subdivide the English fleet into three squadrons. There were three classes of admirals and differentiated by using coloured flags.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information sheet no 055: Squadron Colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>. In 1620 the official [[Flag officer|Flag ranks]] of Admiral, Vice Admiral, and Rear Admiral were legally established that arose directly out of the organisation of the fleet into three parts. [[Admiral of the Fleet (Royal Navy)|Admiral of the Fleet]] as an official flag rank was formally created in 1688.<ref>{{cite web |title=Naval Ranks NMRN Portsmouth |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/naval-ranks |website=www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=The National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=13 February 2019 |location=Portsmouth, England |date=2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Vice-Admiral of the White was a senior rank of the Royal Navy of the United Kingdom, immediately outranked by the rank Vice-Admiral of the Red (see order of precedence below). Such senior ranks or offices generally qualify the Royal Navy officers holding them to be considered ''admirals'', a category that consists of the ranks of commodore, rear admiral, vice admiral and admiral of the fleet.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Costello |first1=Ray |title=Black Salt: Seafarers of African Descent on British Ships |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford England |isbn=9781781386200 |page=222 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46sgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA222&lpg=PA222&dq=Royal+Navy+officers+currently+holding+the+ranks+of+rear+admiral,+vice+admiral+and+admiral+of+the+fleet+are+sometimes+considered+generically+to+be+admirals&source=bl&ots=TUjO9_A59p&sig=ACfU3U0VdGB51vIseBOvUK50Kquz1TlhiA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiYw7nt9pzgAhUgTI8KHTELDN8Q6AEwEXoECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Royal%20Navy%20officers%20currently%20holding%20the%20ranks%20of%20rear%20admiral%2C%20vice%20admiral%20and%20admiral%20of%20the%20fleet%20are%20sometimes%20considered%20generically%20to%20be%20admirals&f=false |language=en}}</ref> From 1688 to 1805 the rank of Vice-Admiral of the White was fifth in the order of precedence; after 1805 it was the sixth. In 1864 it was abolished as a promotional rank.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Services |first1=Library |title=Information sheet no 055 Squadron colours |url=https://www.nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk/sites/default/files/Squadron%20colours.pdf |website=nmrn-portsmouth.org.uk |publisher=National Museum of the Royal Navy |accessdate=7 January 2019 |date=2014}}</ref>\n\n==Order of precedence Admirals of the Colour==\nThe Navy was divided into three squadrons Red, White and Blue in order of seniority. Admirals were appointed to these squadrons and therefore their rank and squadron split the seniority originally into 9 bands then later 10 with \u2018Admiral of the Fleet' as senior to all others..<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1805 to 1864.:\n\n# Admiral of the Fleet,\n# Admiral of the Red Squadron (rank created in 1805)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron \n# '''Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron'''\n# Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nSeniority was therefore from 1688 to 1805.:\n\n# Admiral of the Fleet, (rank created in 1688)\n# Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Vice-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# '''Vice-Admiral of the White Squadron'''\n# Vice-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Red Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the White Squadron\n# Rear-Admiral of the Blue Squadron\n\nAdmirals without an appointment were colloquially referred to as Yellow Admirals. Ships of the Royal Navy flew the Ensign that coincided with the squadron of their commanding officer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Perrin |first1=W. G. (William Gordon) |title=British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device |date=1922 |publisher=Cambridge : The University Press |location=Cambridge, England |pages=76-109 |url=https://archive.org/stream/britishflagsthei00perrrich#page/n111/mode/2up}}</ref>\n\n==Former command flag 1625 to 1805==\n<gallery>\nFile:Flag Vice Admiral of the White 1702 to 1805.png|Vice Admiral of the White Squadron command flag 1625 to 1805.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n# [[List of command flags of the Royal Navy]]\n\n# [[Horatio_Nelson,_1st_Viscount_Nelson]]\n\n==Citations==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n# Perrin, W. G. (William Gordon) (1922). \"Flags of Command: Admirals Flags\". British flags, their early history, and their development at sea; with an account of the origin of the flag as a national device. Cambridge, England: Cambridge : The University Press.\n# Squadron Colours\" (2014), (PDF). National Museum of the Royal Navy.\n\n[[Category:Military ranks of the Royal Navy]]\n", "name_user": "Jmg38", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrder of precedence Admirals of the Colour:links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vice-admiral_of_the_White"}
{"title_page": "Lil' Flip", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name                 = Lil' Flip\n|image                = Lil Flip performing in 2014 2014-04-17 01-34.jpg\n|image_size           = \n|caption              = Weston performing in 2014\n|background           = solo_singer\n|birth_name           = Wesley Eric Weston Jr.\n|birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|3|3}}\n|birth_place          = [[Cloverland, Houston]], [[Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|genre                = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation           = Rapper, record producer, songwriter\n|instruments          = [[Vocals]]\n|years_active         = 1999\u2013present\n|label                = {{hlist|Clover G|SoSouth|[[Fontana Records|Fontana]]|Sucka Free| [[Loud Records|Loud]]| [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]| [[Sony Urban Music|Sony Urban]]|[[Asylum Records|Asylum]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n|associated_acts      ={{flatlist| \n*[[Screwed Up Click]]\n* [[David Banner]]\n*[[Gudda Gudda]]\n*[[Lil' Scrappy]]\n*[[Mike Jones (rapper)|Mike Jones]]\n*[[Mr. Capone-E]]\n*[[Pimp C]]\n*[[Z-Ro]]}}\n|website              = http://lilflipmusic.net/\n}}\n\n'''Wesley Eric Weston Jr.'''<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p437619/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Lil' Flip: Biography|accessdate=August 17, 2009 |year=2008 |website=allmusic }}</ref><ref name=\"lilflip\">{{cite web |first=Becky |last=Proctor |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-52408290.html |title=Lil' Flip OK after shooting, still plans to release album  |publisher=University Wire |location=Houston, Texas |date=April 18, 2002 |format=Fee required |accessdate=August 17, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> (born March 3, 1981),<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> better known by his [[stage name]] '''Lil' Flip''', is an American [[rapping|rapper]]. He embarked on his musical career as a [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] and [[battle rap]]per before earning a record deal with Suckafree Records in 1999. Lil' Flip is best known for his singles \"The Way We Ball\", \"[[Game Over (Flip)|Game Over]]\" and \"[[Sunshine (Lil' Flip song)|Sunshine]]\".\n\n==Musical career==\n===1999\u20132003: ''The Leprechaun'' and ''Undaground Legend''===\nIn 1999 Lil' Flip would sign his first [[record deal]] with independent [[Houston, Texas]] label Suckafree Records. On July 18, 2000 Lil' Flip would release his debut album ''[[The Leprechaun (Lil' Flip album)|The Leprechaun]]'', catching the attention of [[DJ Screw]], who added the rapper into his loose-knit rap group called the [[Screwed Up Click]]. DJ Screw pronounced Lil' Flip \"The Freestyle King.\"<ref name=\"Pandora\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pandora.com/music/artist/lil%2Bflip |title=Lil' Flip Biography |accessdate=2017-05-15 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226095027/http://www.pandora.com/music/artist/lil%2Bflip |archivedate=February 26, 2011 }}. Pandora.com</ref>\n\nIn 2002, [[Columbia Records]] offered Flip a contract and Suckafree a distribution deal. Flip stated \"We felt that they not only respected what we'd already accomplished on our own, but they also saw the big picture of what me as an artist, and Hump and I as Suckafree's CEOs were all about.\" Lil Flip released his second album ''[[Undaground Legend]]'' on August 27, 2002. The album was [[RIAA certification|certified Platinum]] in December 2002. It contained his hit single \"[[Undaground Legend|The Way We Ball]]\". In 2003 Lil' Flip was also featured in [[David Banner]] single \"Like A Pimp\". Then he also made featured appearance on [[Yung Wun]]'s charting single \"[[Tear It Up (Yung Wun song)|Tear It Up]]\". He also made another appearance on [[Three 6 Mafia]] single \"Ridin' Spinners\" that made the charts. In 2003, he also did a track with [[Ludacris]] called \"Screwed Up\".\n\n===2004\u201305: ''U Gotta Feel Me''===\nIn 2004 Lil' Flip released his third album & first double-disc album ''[[U Gotta Feel Me]]'', his most successful album to date. Lil' Flip's label [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] restructured and Flip ended up at [[Sony Urban Music]], which he believed could promote his work better. The first single from the album was \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\". After that he quickly released his second single, \"[[U Gotta Feel Me|Sunshine]]\" featuring Lea Sunshine. This album sold 198,000 domestic copies in its first week and was certified double Platinum by August, 2004. Lil' Flip also made an appearance on the \"Naughty Girl (Remix)\" with [[Beyonc\u00e9]] in 2004. He was also featured on [[Chingy]]'s ''[[Powerballin']]'' on the remix of [[Chingy]]'s successful hit single \"[[Balla Baby]]\". In 2004 he also made a remix to his hit single \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\" which featured [[Young Buck]] and [[Bun B]]. He also made a guest appearance on [[Nelly]]'s successful 2004 album \"[[Sweat (Nelly album)|Sweat]]\". He also collaborated with [[Jim Jones]] and [[Game (rapper)|The Game]] on the \"Certified Gangstas (Remix)\" in 2004. In 2005 Lil' Flip & [[Z-Ro]] made a collaboration album titled ''[[Kings of the South]]''. Also in 2005 Lil' Flip was featured in [[Chamillionaire]]'s first single \"[[Turn It Up (Chamillionaire song)|Turn It Up]]\". He was also featured in the remix of [[Bun B]]'s single \"[[Draped Up]]\".<ref name=\"Pandora\" />\n\n===2007\u201309: ''I Need Mine'' and ''Respect Me''===\nIn 2007 Lil' Flip left [[Columbia records]], founding his own label Clover G Records & would sign a new label deal with [[Asylum Records|Asylum]] & [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]. Lil' Flip would release his third album & second double-disc album titled ''[[I Need Mine]]'' on March 27, 2007, the album debuted at number 15 on the Billboard 200 with 43,000 copies sold in its first week. Only two singles were released from the album, \"What It Do\" & \"[[Ghetto Mindstate (Can't Get Away)]]\".\n\nHis planned fifth album ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'' was originally set to be released as early as 2007, but was pushed back many times. Lil' Flip released two \"album-before-the-album's\" in 2009 to help promote the release of ''[[Ahead of My Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Arnold |first=Paul W |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9833/title.lil-flip-talks-respect-me-rap-a-lot-records |title=Lil Flip Talks \"Respect Me,\" Rap-A-Lot Records &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2009-09-18 |accessdate=2011-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703134136/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9833/title.lil-flip-talks-respect-me-rap-a-lot-records |archivedate=2011-07-03 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/10/chicken-n-beer-where-are-they-now.html?cid=rss#!021012-celebs-cake-lil-flip  \"Chicken N Beer: Where are they now?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142013/http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/10/chicken-n-beer-where-are-they-now.html?cid=rss |date=2014-04-13 }} BET</ref> On September 29, 2009 Lil' Flip would release his fifth album titled ''[[Respect Me (Lil' Flip album)|Respect Me]]'' to promote ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'', it would be distributed by High Powered Entertainment & [[E1 Music]]. On December 24, 2009 Lil' Flip would release his first independent album titled ''[[Underground Legend 2]]'' to promote ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'', it would be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/underground-legend-2/id348246782 |title=iTunes - Music - Underground Legend 2 by Lil' Flip. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105143056/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/underground-legend-2/id348246782 |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present: More independent releases===\nOn July 6, 2010 Lil' Flip would release ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'' as his second independent album, and debuted his artist Damienn jones \"Beauty and the Beast\" album, it would be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records.\n\nOn October 31, 2013 Lil' Flip released his third independent album ''The Black Dr. Kevorkian'', it would also be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records & would sell over 10,000 copies its first week.\n\nOn March 17, 2015 Lil' Flip released his sixth album titled ''El Jefe'', it was distributed by SoSouth Records.<ref name=\"apple.com\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/el-jefe/id967506405|title=El Jefe|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120051218/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/el-jefe/id967506405|archivedate=2015-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/El-Jefe-Explicit-Lil-Flip/dp/B00TPPZ60K|title=Amazon.com: El Jefe [Explicit]: Lil' Flip: MP3 Downloads|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20151119052224/https://www.amazon.com/El-Jefe-Explicit-Lil-Flip/dp/B00TPPZ60K|archivedate=2015-11-19}}</ref> The lead single from the album was titled \"Game Over II\", which was sequel to his single \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/game-over-ii-single/id917464922|title=Game Over II - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121001725/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/game-over-ii-single/id917464922|archivedate=2015-11-21}}</ref> The second single from the album, was titled \"In My Pimp C Voice\", which was a dedication song towards deceased artist [[Pimp C]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-my-pimp-c-voice-single/id947959320|title=In My Pimp C Voice - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120205208/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-my-pimp-c-voice-single/id947959320|archivedate=2015-11-20}}</ref> The third single from the album, was titled \"Bestfriend\" the single would feature artist's E.J. & Rev City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopweekly.com/lil-flip-bestfriend-feat-e-j-rev-city/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120075548/http://www.hiphopweekly.com/lil-flip-bestfriend-feat-e-j-rev-city/ |archivedate=2015-11-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/bestfriend-feat.-e.j.-rev/id966063471|title=Bestfriend (feat. E.J. & Rev City) - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518100528/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/bestfriend-feat.-e.j.-rev/id966063471|archivedate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Clover G Records===\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Clover G Records\n| image       = \n| image_bg    = \n| parent      = \n| founded     = 2004\n| founder     = Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston Jr. (CEO) & (President)\n| status      = Active\n| distributor = [[Asylum Records|Asylum]], [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] <small>(2007-2008)</small> \n| genre       = [[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Crunk]], [[R&B]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[Houston, Texas]] <small>(2004-present)</small>\n| url         = \n}}\n'''Clover G Records''' or '''Clover G La Familia''' is a record label owned by [[Houston, Texas]] rapper Lil' Flip, it was created in 2004.\n\n===Fashion designing===\nIn 2004 Lil' Flip released his shoe line titled \"Clover Footwear\" which is branded off his self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sojones.com/news/lil-flp-launches-clover-footwear-and-clothing/|title=Lil Flip Launches Clover Footwear and Clothing Line|work=SoJones|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413202328/http://sojones.com/news/lil-flp-launches-clover-footwear-and-clothing/|archivedate=2015-04-13}}</ref> Lil' Flip also has a fashion clothing line titled \"Clover G Clothing\" which is also branded off his self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cloverg.com/clover-g-clothing.html|title=Clover G Clothing - Online|work=Clover G Clothing|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416110333/http://www.cloverg.com/clover-g-clothing.html|archivedate=2015-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\nOn April 15, 2014 Lil' Flip released his first book titled ''Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You!'', the book was released with a soundtrack album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Let-Music-Industry-Fool-ebook/dp/B00JQGR4GW|title=Amazon.com: Don't Let The Music Industry Fool You! eBook: Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston: Kindle Store|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305144932/http://www.amazon.com/Dont-Let-Music-Industry-Fool-ebook/dp/B00JQGR4GW|archivedate=2016-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dont-let-music-industry-fool/id868215193|title=Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You (Soundtrack)|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306050155/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dont-let-music-industry-fool/id868215193|archivedate=2016-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lil' Flip discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 2000: ''[[The Leprechaun (Lil' Flip album)|The Leprechaun]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Undaground Legend]]''\n* 2004: ''[[U Gotta Feel Me]]''\n* 2007: ''[[I Need Mine]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Respect Me (Lil' Flip album)|Respect Me]]''\n* 2009: ''Underground Legend 2''\n* 2010: ''[[Ahead of My Time]]''\n* 2013: ''The Black Dr. Kevorkian''\n* 2015: ''El Jefe''\n* 2016: ''The Art of Freestyle''\n* 2018: ''King''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/king/1363021753|title=iTunes - Music - King by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2018-03-24|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503163606/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/king/1363021753|archivedate=2018-05-03}}</ref>\n* 2018: ''Life''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/life/1364226001|title=iTunes - Music - Life by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2018-03-26|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403053611/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/life/1364226001|archivedate=2018-04-03}}</ref>\n* 2019: ''The Art of Freestyle 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-art-of-freestyle-vol-2/1485662180|title=iTunes - Music - The Art of Freestyle 2 by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n* 2019: ''The Music Machine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-music-machine/1489376945|title=iTunes - Music - The Music Machine by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''Feelings''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/feelings/1499022903|title=iTunes - Music - Feelings by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''No Feelings''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/no-feelings/1498703789|title=iTunes - Music - No Feelings by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''The Leprechaun 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-leprechaun-2/1503091337|title=iTunes - Music - The Leprechaun 2 by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n* 2005: ''[[Kings of the South]]'' <small>(with [[Z-Ro]])</small>\n* 2006: ''[[Connected (Lil Flip & Mr. Capone-E album)|Connected]]'' <small>(with [[Mr. Capone-E]])</small>\n* 2007: ''[[Still Connected]]'' <small>(with Mr. Capone-E)</small>\n* 2008: ''[[All Eyez on Us]]'' <small>(with [[Young Noble]])</small>\n* 2009: ''[[Certified (Lil' Flip & Gudda Gudda album)|Certified]]'' <small>(with [[Gudda Gudda]])</small>\n\n===Soundtrack album===\n* 2014: ''Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You''\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Don't Let The Music Industry Fool You!'' by Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston (2014: Harris Royal Bloodline Publishing, 15 April 2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140803043747/http://www.cloverg.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Lil' Flip}}\n{{Screwed Up Click}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lil' Flip}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Houston]]\n[[Category:Screwed Up Click members]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Houston]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Texas]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n|name                 = Lil' Flip\n|image                = Lil Flip performing in 2014 2014-04-17 01-34.jpg\n|image_size           = \n|caption              = Weston performing in 2014\n|background           = solo_singer\n|birth_name           = Wesley Eric Weston Jr.\n|birth_date           = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|3|3}}\n|birth_place          = [[Cloverland, Houston]], [[Texas]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n|genre                = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|occupation           = Rapper, record producer, songwriter\n|instruments          = [[Vocals]]\n|years_active         = 1999\u2013present\n|label                = {{hlist|Clover G|SoSouth|[[Fontana Records|Fontana]]|Sucka Free| [[Loud Records|Loud]]| [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]| [[Sony Urban Music|Sony Urban]]|[[Asylum Records|Asylum]]|[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]}}\n|associated_acts      ={{flatlist| \n*[[Screwed Up Click]]\n* [[David Banner]]\n*[[Gudda Gudda]]\n*[[Lil' Scrappy]]\n*[[Mike Jones (rapper)|Mike Jones]]\n*[[Mr. Capone-E]]\n*[[Pimp C]]\n*[[Z-Ro]]}}\n|website              = http://lilflipmusic.net/\n}}\n\n'''Wesley Eric Weston Jr.'''<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web |last=Birchmeier|first=Jason|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p437619/biography|pure_url=yes}}|title=Lil' Flip: Biography|accessdate=August 17, 2009 |year=2008 |website=allmusic }}</ref><ref name=\"lilflip\">{{cite web |first=Becky |last=Proctor |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-52408290.html |title=Lil' Flip OK after shooting, still plans to release album  |publisher=University Wire |location=Houston, Texas |date=April 18, 2002 |format=Fee required |accessdate=August 17, 2009 }}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> (born March 3, 1981),<ref name=\"allmusic\"/> better known by his [[stage name]] '''Lil' Flip''', is an American [[rapping|rapper]]. He embarked on his musical career as a [[Freestyle rap|freestyle]] and [[battle rap]]per before earning a record deal with Suckafree Records in 1999. Lil' Flip is best known for his singles \"The Way We Ball\", \"[[Game Over (Flip)|Game Over]]\" and \"[[Sunshine (Lil' Flip song)|Sunshine]]\".\n\n==Musical career==\n===1999\u20132003: ''The Leprechaun'' and ''Undaground Legend''===\nIn 1999 Lil' Flip and Dat Boy Zo would sign his first [[record deal]] with independent [[Houston, Texas]] label Suckafree Records. On July 18, 2000 Lil' Flip would release his debut album ''[[The Leprechaun (Lil' Flip album)|The Leprechaun]]'', catching the attention of [[DJ Screw]], who added the rapper into his loose-knit rap group called the [[Screwed Up Click]]. DJ Screw pronounced Lil' Flip \"The Freestyle King.\"<ref name=\"Pandora\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pandora.com/music/artist/lil%2Bflip |title=Lil' Flip Biography |accessdate=2017-05-15 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226095027/http://www.pandora.com/music/artist/lil%2Bflip |archivedate=February 26, 2011 }}. Pandora.com</ref>\n\nIn 2002, [[Columbia Records]] offered Flip a contract and Suckafree a distribution deal. Flip stated \"We felt that they not only respected what we'd already accomplished on our own, but they also saw the big picture of what me as an artist, and Hump and I as Suckafree's CEOs were all about.\" Lil Flip released his second album ''[[Undaground Legend]]'' on August 27, 2002. The album was [[RIAA certification|certified Platinum]] in December 2002. It contained his hit single \"[[Undaground Legend|The Way We Ball]]\". In 2003 Lil' Flip was also featured in [[David Banner]] single \"Like A Pimp\". Then he also made featured appearance on [[Yung Wun]]'s charting single \"[[Tear It Up (Yung Wun song)|Tear It Up]]\". He also made another appearance on [[Three 6 Mafia]] single \"Ridin' Spinners\" that made the charts. In 2003, he also did a track with [[Ludacris]] called \"Screwed Up\".\n\n===2004\u201305: ''U Gotta Feel Me''===\nIn 2004 Lil' Flip released his third album & first double-disc album ''[[U Gotta Feel Me]]'', his most successful album to date. Lil' Flip's label [[Columbia Records|Columbia]] restructured and Flip ended up at [[Sony Urban Music]], which he believed could promote his work better. The first single from the album was \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\". After that he quickly released his second single, \"[[U Gotta Feel Me|Sunshine]]\" featuring Lea Sunshine. This album sold 198,000 domestic copies in its first week and was certified double Platinum by August, 2004. Lil' Flip also made an appearance on the \"Naughty Girl (Remix)\" with [[Beyonc\u00e9]] in 2004. He was also featured on [[Chingy]]'s ''[[Powerballin']]'' on the remix of [[Chingy]]'s successful hit single \"[[Balla Baby]]\". In 2004 he also made a remix to his hit single \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\" which featured [[Young Buck]] and [[Bun B]]. He also made a guest appearance on [[Nelly]]'s successful 2004 album \"[[Sweat (Nelly album)|Sweat]]\". He also collaborated with [[Jim Jones]] and [[Game (rapper)|The Game]] on the \"Certified Gangstas (Remix)\" in 2004. In 2005 Lil' Flip & [[Z-Ro]] made a collaboration album titled ''[[Kings of the South]]''. Also in 2005 Lil' Flip was featured in [[Chamillionaire]]'s first single \"[[Turn It Up (Chamillionaire song)|Turn It Up]]\". He was also featured in the remix of [[Bun B]]'s single \"[[Draped Up]]\".<ref name=\"Pandora\" />\n\n===2007\u201309: ''I Need Mine'' and ''Respect Me''===\nIn 2007 Lil' Flip left [[Columbia records]], founding his own label Clover G Records & would sign a new label deal with [[Asylum Records|Asylum]] & [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]. Lil' Flip would release his third album & second double-disc album titled ''[[I Need Mine]]'' on March 27, 2007, the album debuted at number 15 on the Billboard 200 with 43,000 copies sold in its first week. Only two singles were released from the album, \"What It Do\" & \"[[Ghetto Mindstate (Can't Get Away)]]\".\n\nHis planned fifth album ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'' was originally set to be released as early as 2007, but was pushed back many times. Lil' Flip released two \"album-before-the-album's\" in 2009 to help promote the release of ''[[Ahead of My Time]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Arnold |first=Paul W |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9833/title.lil-flip-talks-respect-me-rap-a-lot-records |title=Lil Flip Talks \"Respect Me,\" Rap-A-Lot Records &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHop DX |date=2009-09-18 |accessdate=2011-11-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703134136/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9833/title.lil-flip-talks-respect-me-rap-a-lot-records |archivedate=2011-07-03 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/10/chicken-n-beer-where-are-they-now.html?cid=rss#!021012-celebs-cake-lil-flip  \"Chicken N Beer: Where are they now?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413142013/http://www.bet.com/music/photos/2013/10/chicken-n-beer-where-are-they-now.html?cid=rss |date=2014-04-13 }} BET</ref> On September 29, 2009 Lil' Flip would release his fifth album titled ''[[Respect Me (Lil' Flip album)|Respect Me]]'' to promote ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'', it would be distributed by High Powered Entertainment & [[E1 Music]]. On December 24, 2009 Lil' Flip would release his first independent album titled ''[[Underground Legend 2]]'' to promote ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'', it would be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/underground-legend-2/id348246782 |title=iTunes - Music - Underground Legend 2 by Lil' Flip. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105143056/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/underground-legend-2/id348246782 |archivedate=2012-11-05 }}</ref>\n\n===2010\u2013present: More independent releases===\nOn July 6, 2010 Lil' Flip would release ''[[Ahead of My Time]]'' as his second independent album, and debuted his artist Damienn jones \"Beauty and the Beast\" album, it would be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records.\n\nOn October 31, 2013 Lil' Flip released his third independent album ''The Black Dr. Kevorkian'', it would also be distributed independently by Lil' Flip's self-owned label Clover G Records & would sell over 10,000 copies its first week.\n\nOn March 17, 2015 Lil' Flip released his sixth album titled ''El Jefe'', it was distributed by SoSouth Records.<ref name=\"apple.com\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/el-jefe/id967506405|title=El Jefe|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120051218/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/el-jefe/id967506405|archivedate=2015-11-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/El-Jefe-Explicit-Lil-Flip/dp/B00TPPZ60K|title=Amazon.com: El Jefe [Explicit]: Lil' Flip: MP3 Downloads|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20151119052224/https://www.amazon.com/El-Jefe-Explicit-Lil-Flip/dp/B00TPPZ60K|archivedate=2015-11-19}}</ref> The lead single from the album was titled \"Game Over II\", which was sequel to his single \"[[Game Over (Flip)]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/game-over-ii-single/id917464922|title=Game Over II - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121001725/https://itunes.apple.com/nz/album/game-over-ii-single/id917464922|archivedate=2015-11-21}}</ref> The second single from the album, was titled \"In My Pimp C Voice\", which was a dedication song towards deceased artist [[Pimp C]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-my-pimp-c-voice-single/id947959320|title=In My Pimp C Voice - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120205208/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/in-my-pimp-c-voice-single/id947959320|archivedate=2015-11-20}}</ref> The third single from the album, was titled \"Bestfriend\" the single would feature artist's E.J. & Rev City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hiphopweekly.com/lil-flip-bestfriend-feat-e-j-rev-city/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-11-19 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120075548/http://www.hiphopweekly.com/lil-flip-bestfriend-feat-e-j-rev-city/ |archivedate=2015-11-20 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/bestfriend-feat.-e.j.-rev/id966063471|title=Bestfriend (feat. E.J. & Rev City) - Single|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518100528/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/bestfriend-feat.-e.j.-rev/id966063471|archivedate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\n==Other ventures==\n===Clover G Records===\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Clover G Records\n| image       = \n| image_bg    = \n| parent      = \n| founded     = 2004\n| founder     = Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston Jr. (CEO) & (President)\n| status      = Active\n| distributor = [[Asylum Records|Asylum]], [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]] <small>(2007-2008)</small> \n| genre       = [[Hip hop music|Hip-hop]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Crunk]], [[R&B]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[Houston, Texas]] <small>(2004-present)</small>\n| url         = \n}}\n'''Clover G Records''' or '''Clover G La Familia''' is a record label owned by [[Houston, Texas]] rapper Lil' Flip, it was created in 2004.\n\n===Fashion designing===\nIn 2004 Lil' Flip released his shoe line titled \"Clover Footwear\" which is branded off his self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sojones.com/news/lil-flp-launches-clover-footwear-and-clothing/|title=Lil Flip Launches Clover Footwear and Clothing Line|work=SoJones|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413202328/http://sojones.com/news/lil-flp-launches-clover-footwear-and-clothing/|archivedate=2015-04-13}}</ref> Lil' Flip also has a fashion clothing line titled \"Clover G Clothing\" which is also branded off his self-owned label Clover G Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cloverg.com/clover-g-clothing.html|title=Clover G Clothing - Online|work=Clover G Clothing|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150416110333/http://www.cloverg.com/clover-g-clothing.html|archivedate=2015-04-16}}</ref>\n\n===Author===\nOn April 15, 2014 Lil' Flip released his first book titled ''Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You!'', the book was released with a soundtrack album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Let-Music-Industry-Fool-ebook/dp/B00JQGR4GW|title=Amazon.com: Don't Let The Music Industry Fool You! eBook: Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston: Kindle Store|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305144932/http://www.amazon.com/Dont-Let-Music-Industry-Fool-ebook/dp/B00JQGR4GW|archivedate=2016-03-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dont-let-music-industry-fool/id868215193|title=Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You (Soundtrack)|work=iTunes|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306050155/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/dont-let-music-industry-fool/id868215193|archivedate=2016-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Lil' Flip discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* 2000: ''[[The Leprechaun (Lil' Flip album)|The Leprechaun]]''\n* 2002: ''[[Undaground Legend]]''\n* 2004: ''[[U Gotta Feel Me]]''\n* 2007: ''[[I Need Mine]]''\n* 2009: ''[[Respect Me (Lil' Flip album)|Respect Me]]''\n* 2009: ''Underground Legend 2''\n* 2010: ''[[Ahead of My Time]]''\n* 2013: ''The Black Dr. Kevorkian''\n* 2015: ''El Jefe''\n* 2016: ''The Art of Freestyle''\n* 2018: ''King''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/king/1363021753|title=iTunes - Music - King by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2018-03-24|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180503163606/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/king/1363021753|archivedate=2018-05-03}}</ref>\n* 2018: ''Life''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/life/1364226001|title=iTunes - Music - Life by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2018-03-26|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403053611/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/life/1364226001|archivedate=2018-04-03}}</ref>\n* 2019: ''The Art of Freestyle 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-art-of-freestyle-vol-2/1485662180|title=iTunes - Music - The Art of Freestyle 2 by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2019-10-31}}</ref>\n* 2019: ''The Music Machine''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-music-machine/1489376945|title=iTunes - Music - The Music Machine by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''Feelings''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/feelings/1499022903|title=iTunes - Music - Feelings by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''No Feelings''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/no-feelings/1498703789|title=iTunes - Music - No Feelings by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n* 2020: ''The Leprechaun 2''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-leprechaun-2/1503091337|title=iTunes - Music - The Leprechaun 2 by Lil' Flip|publisher=iTunes|accessdate=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n* 2005: ''[[Kings of the South]]'' <small>(with [[Z-Ro]])</small>\n* 2006: ''[[Connected (Lil Flip & Mr. Capone-E album)|Connected]]'' <small>(with [[Mr. Capone-E]])</small>\n* 2007: ''[[Still Connected]]'' <small>(with Mr. Capone-E)</small>\n* 2008: ''[[All Eyez on Us]]'' <small>(with [[Young Noble]])</small>\n* 2009: ''[[Certified (Lil' Flip & Gudda Gudda album)|Certified]]'' <small>(with [[Gudda Gudda]])</small>\n\n===Soundtrack album===\n* 2014: ''Don't Let the Music Industry Fool You''\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Don't Let The Music Industry Fool You!'' by Wesley \"Lil' Flip\" Weston (2014: Harris Royal Bloodline Publishing, 15 April 2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140803043747/http://www.cloverg.com/ Official website]\n\n{{Lil' Flip}}\n{{Screwed Up Click}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lil' Flip}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Houston]]\n[[Category:Screwed Up Click members]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Warner Records artists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Houston]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American hip hop 