"At Your Age\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Roc (TV series)|Roc]]''\n|  Carol\n| Episode: \"Roc Throws Joey Out\"\n|-\n| 1992\n| ''[[Tales from the Crypt (film)|Tales from the Crypt]]''\n| Mercedes\n| Episode: \"Werewolf Concerto\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Out All Night (TV series)|Out All Night]]''\n| Victoria\n|Episode: \"Mall in the Family\"\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[The Sinbad Show]]''\n| Denise\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 1994\n| ''[[Hangin' with Mr. Cooper]]''\n| Denise\n|Episode: \"The Courtship of Mark Cooper\"\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[The Wayans Bros.]]''\n| Lisa \n| Series regular, 13 episodes\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Outer Limits (1995 TV series)|The Outer Limits]] ''\n| Beth Carter\n| Episode: \"The Awakening\"\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Division]]''\n| Inspector Angela Reide\n| Series regular, 22 episodes\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Reed Between the Lines]] ''\n|Sherri \n| Episode: \"Let's Talk About Affairs\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Training Day (TV series)|Training Day]]''\n|Mrs. Craig\n|Recurring role, 3 episodes \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Alone Together (TV series)|Alone Together]] ''\n|Rose\n| Episode: \"Dinner Party\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[David Makes Man]]''\n|Alma\n|Recurring role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0005375|name=Lela Rochon}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rochon, Lela}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Little Rock, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "2601:46:200:27f7:7436:d9d8:3a39:4ab0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lela_Rochon"}
{"title_page": "Cappadonna", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Cappadonna\n| image            = Cappadonna2.png\n| background       = solo_singer <!-- includes rappers -->\n| birth_name       = Darryl Hill\n| alias            = Cappachino\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1969|09|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| occupation       = Rapper\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 1990\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=2|title=Cappadonna Biography at Wu-Tang Corp. - The Official Site of the Wu-Tang Clan|first=Wu-Tang|last=Corp.|website=www.wutang-corp.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n| label            = [[Razor Sharp Records]]/[[Sony Music Entertainment Inc.|SME Records]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[List of Wu-Tang Clan affiliates|Wu-Tang Killa Beez]]\n| management       = Honor Management Group\n}}\n\n'''Darryl Hill''' (born September 18, 1969), better known by his stage name '''Cappadonna''', is an [[United States|American]] [[rapper]]. He is a member of the hip-hop collective the [[Wu-Tang Clan]]<ref name=\"Wu Tang Status\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.30967/title.rza-reveals-cappadonnas-status-in-wu-tang-clan |title=RZA Reveals Cappadonna's Status In Wu-Tang Clan |publisher=HipHopDX |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref> and is a member of the rap group [[Theodore Unit]] together with [[Ghostface Killah]].\n\n==Career==\nCappadonna (also known as Cappachino) was known to the future members of the Wu-Tang Clan, and had been [[U-God]]'s mentor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilxor.com/ILX/ThreadSelectedControllerServlet?boardid=41&threadid=39731|title=XXL Article On The Making Of \"Only Built 4 Cuban Linx\".|website=www.ilxor.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> However, Cappadonna went to prison and was replaced in the group by [[Method Man]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Th4TZsr8I4 |title=RZA Explains The Origin Of The Wu-Tang To Funkmaster Flex |publisher=YouTube |date= |access-date=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n\nCappadonna made his recording debut as an affiliate of the Wu-Tang Clan on [[Raekwon]]'s 1995 single \"[[Ice Cream (Raekwon song)|Ice Cream]]\" on ''[[Only Built for Cuban Linx...]]''. He was also a guest star, along with Raekwon, on [[Ghostface Killah]]'s solo debut album, ''[[Ironman (Ghostface Killah album)|Ironman]]''. He made his first appearance on a Wu-Tang Clan album in 1997 on ''[[Wu-Tang Forever]]'' on the single \"[[Triumph (Wu-Tang Clan song)|Triumph]]\". Following his appearance on ''Forever'', he contributed significantly{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=December 2018}} to the group's third studio album, ''[[The W]]'', at which point his appearances were no longer marked with \"Featuring Cappadonna\", as they had been on ''Forever''. After a falling-out with [[RZA]] the next year over royalties, he did not appear at all on the group's subsequent album ''[[Iron Flag]]''. He reunited with the group for their concert at 2004's [[Rock the Bells]], and appeared on 2007's ''[[8 Diagrams]]''.\n\nCappadonna's status as a Wu-Tang member or as a featured artist has varied throughout the years, while long referred to by both the group and fans as the \"Unofficial Tenth Member\". Also, while his vocals on ''8 Diagrams'' were not marked with \"Feat. Cappadonna\", much like ''The W'', he does not appear on the front cover with the original eight living members, and is not featured in the album's booklet with a picture, although he is included in the group's shout-outs sections. In a press conference held October 2, 2014, at Warner Studios for the upcoming release of the Wu-Tang Clan's ''A Better Tomorrow album'', RZA clarified any misunderstanding of Cappadonna's affiliation with Wu-Tang Clan, stating that Cappadonna has been an official member of Wu-Tang Clan since ''8 Diagrams''.<ref name=\"Wu Tang Status\"/>\n\nCappadonna's first solo effort was 1998's ''[[The Pillage]]'' which debuted and peaked at number 3 on the charts and certified Gold. His follow-up - 2001's ''[[The Yin and the Yang|The Ying and The Yang]]'' - debuted at number 51 on the charts. Staying vigilant in his support of The Clan, he then featured on over 25 releases including classics from Raekwon, Method Man and Ghostface. \n \nKnown for his colorful wardrobe, he frequently refers to fashion designers and his large collection of boutique clothing in his raps.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 2019 Cappadonna was featured in ''[[Wu-Tang Clan: Of Mics and Men]],'' a documentary in honor of the 25th anniversary of Wu-Tang Clan's debut album, ''Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/wu-tang-clan-of-mics-and-men-interview.html|title=The Wu-Tang Clan Looks Back on 25 Years|last=|first=|date=|website=www.vulture.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:350px;\"|Album Name\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Release Date\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Certifications\n|-\n|''[[The Pillage]]'' \n|March 24, 1998\n|\nRIAA: Gold <ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Yin and the Yang]]''\n|April 3, 2001\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Struggle (Cappadonna album)|The Struggle]]''\n|October 7, 2003\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Cappatilize Project]]''\n|July 22, 2008\n|\n|-\n|''[[Slang Prostitution]]''\n|January 27, 2009\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Pilgrimage (album)|The Pilgrimage]]''\n|November 15, 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B005VGU7LU |title=The Pilgrimage [Explicit&#93;: Cappadonna: MP3 Downloads |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-05}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|''[[Eyrth, Wynd and Fyre]]''\n|February 26, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undergroundhiphop.com/cappadonna-eyrth-wynd-fyre/RBC410CD/ |title=Cappadonna - Eyrth, Wynd & Fyre - Audio CD [2CD&#93; - Underground Hip Hop - Store |publisher=Underground Hip Hop |date= |accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|''Hook Off''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hook-off-collectors-edition/id891699751|title=Hook Off (Collectors Edition) by Cappadonna on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n|June 17, 2014\n|\n|-\n|''The Pillage 2''\n|November 27, 2015\n|\n|-\n|''Ear Candy''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glfent.com/product-page/ear-candy|title=Ear Candy by Cappadonna on GLF Ent|website=www.glfent.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n|July 20, 2018\n|\n|}\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:350px;\"|Album Name\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Release Date\n|-\n|''[[Ironman (Ghostface Killah album)|Ironman]]'' <small>([[Ghostface Killah]] album, billed alongside [[Raekwon]])</small>\n|1996\n|-\n|''Iron Fist Pillage'' (Soundtrack)\n|2001\n|-\n|''[[718 (album)|718]]'' <small>(with [[Theodore Unit]])</small>\n|2004\n|-\n|''Wu South Vl. 1'' (with Ratched Rush)\n|2005\n|-\n|''Wu South Vl. 2'' (with Ratched Rush)\n|2009\n|-\n|''The 2nd Coming'' <small>(with [[Bronze Nazareth]], [[Canibus]], M-Eighty, Nino Grave & [[Planet Asia]], as The Almighty)</small>\n|2013\n|}\n\n===Singles and EPs===\n\n* 1996 \"Taking Drastic Measures\"\n* 1996 ''Don't Be a Menace'' soundtrack - track \"Winter Warz\"\n* 1998 \"Slang Editorial\"\n* 1998 \"Run\"\n* 1999 \"Black Boy\"\n* 2001 \"Super Model\"\n* 2007 \"Don't Turn Around\"\n* 2009 \"Somebody's Got To Go\"\n* 2011 \"Cuban Link Kings\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070516045934/http://riotsound.com/hip-hop/rap/interviews/Cappadonna/index.php Cappadonna Interview]\n* [http://www.fakeshoredrive.blogspot.com/2007/12/fake-shore-drive-vs-cappadonna.html Cappadonna Interview with Fake Shore Drive]\n{{Cappadonna}}\n{{Wu-Tang Clan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan members]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York City]]\n[[Category:American beatboxers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Cappadonna\n| image            = Cappadonna2.png\n| background       = solo_singer <!-- includes rappers -->\n| birth_name       = Darryl Hill\n| alias            = Cappachino\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1969|09|18}}\n| origin           = [[Staten Island]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 1995\u2013present<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=2|title=Cappadonna Biography at Wu-Tang Corp. - The Official Site of the Wu-Tang Clan|first=Wu-Tang|last=Corp.|website=www.wutang-corp.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n| label            = [[Razor Sharp Records]]/[[Sony Music Entertainment Inc.|SME Records]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[List of Wu-Tang Clan affiliates|Wu-Tang Killa Beez]]\n| management       = Honor Management Group\n}}\n\n'''Darryl Hill''' (born September 18, 1969), better known by his stage name '''Cappadonna''', is an [[United States|American]] [[rapper]]. He is a member of the hip-hop collective the [[Wu-Tang Clan]]<ref name=\"Wu Tang Status\">{{cite web|author= |url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.30967/title.rza-reveals-cappadonnas-status-in-wu-tang-clan |title=RZA Reveals Cappadonna's Status In Wu-Tang Clan |publisher=HipHopDX |accessdate=2014-10-17}}</ref> and is a member of the rap group [[Theodore Unit]] together with [[Ghostface Killah]].\n\n==Career==\nCappadonna (also known as Cappachino) was known to the future members of the Wu-Tang Clan, and had been [[U-God]]'s mentor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ilxor.com/ILX/ThreadSelectedControllerServlet?boardid=41&threadid=39731|title=XXL Article On The Making Of \"Only Built 4 Cuban Linx\".|website=www.ilxor.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> However, Cappadonna went to prison and was replaced in the group by [[Method Man]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1Th4TZsr8I4 |title=RZA Explains The Origin Of The Wu-Tang To Funkmaster Flex |publisher=YouTube |date= |access-date=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n\nCappadonna made his recording debut as an affiliate of the Wu-Tang Clan on [[Raekwon]]'s 1995 single \"[[Ice Cream (Raekwon song)|Ice Cream]]\" on ''[[Only Built for Cuban Linx...]]''. He was also a guest star, along with Raekwon, on [[Ghostface Killah]]'s solo debut album, ''[[Ironman (Ghostface Killah album)|Ironman]]''. He made his first appearance on a Wu-Tang Clan album in 1997 on ''[[Wu-Tang Forever]]'' on the single \"[[Triumph (Wu-Tang Clan song)|Triumph]]\". Following his appearance on ''Forever'', he contributed significantly{{Clarify|reason=vague|date=December 2018}} to the group's third studio album, ''[[The W]]'', at which point his appearances were no longer marked with \"Featuring Cappadonna\", as they had been on ''Forever''. After a falling-out with [[RZA]] the next year over royalties, he did not appear at all on the group's subsequent album ''[[Iron Flag]]''. He reunited with the group for their concert at 2004's [[Rock the Bells]], and appeared on 2007's ''[[8 Diagrams]]''.\n\nCappadonna's status as a Wu-Tang member or as a featured artist has varied throughout the years, while long referred to by both the group and fans as the \"Unofficial Tenth Member\". Also, while his vocals on ''8 Diagrams'' were not marked with \"Feat. Cappadonna\", much like ''The W'', he does not appear on the front cover with the original eight living members, and is not featured in the album's booklet with a picture, although he is included in the group's shout-outs sections. In a press conference held October 2, 2014, at Warner Studios for the upcoming release of the Wu-Tang Clan's ''A Better Tomorrow album'', RZA clarified any misunderstanding of Cappadonna's affiliation with Wu-Tang Clan, stating that Cappadonna has been an official member of Wu-Tang Clan since ''8 Diagrams''.<ref name=\"Wu Tang Status\"/>\n\nCappadonna's first solo effort was 1998's ''[[The Pillage]]'' which debuted and peaked at number 3 on the charts and certified Gold. His follow-up - 2001's ''[[The Yin and the Yang|The Ying and The Yang]]'' - debuted at number 51 on the charts. Staying vigilant in his support of The Clan, he then featured on over 25 releases including classics from Raekwon, Method Man and Ghostface. \n \nKnown for his colorful wardrobe, he frequently refers to fashion designers and his large collection of boutique clothing in his raps.{{Citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn 2019 Cappadonna was featured in ''[[Wu-Tang Clan: Of Mics and Men]],'' a documentary in honor of the 25th anniversary of Wu-Tang Clan's debut album, ''Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers).''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/02/wu-tang-clan-of-mics-and-men-interview.html|title=The Wu-Tang Clan Looks Back on 25 Years|last=|first=|date=|website=www.vulture.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-02-09}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:350px;\"|Album Name\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Release Date\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Certifications\n|-\n|''[[The Pillage]]'' \n|March 24, 1998\n|\nRIAA: Gold <ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|publisher=|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[The Yin and the Yang]]''\n|April 3, 2001\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Struggle (Cappadonna album)|The Struggle]]''\n|October 7, 2003\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Cappatilize Project]]''\n|July 22, 2008\n|\n|-\n|''[[Slang Prostitution]]''\n|January 27, 2009\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Pilgrimage (album)|The Pilgrimage]]''\n|November 15, 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B005VGU7LU |title=The Pilgrimage [Explicit&#93;: Cappadonna: MP3 Downloads |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=2012-05-05}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|''[[Eyrth, Wynd and Fyre]]''\n|February 26, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.undergroundhiphop.com/cappadonna-eyrth-wynd-fyre/RBC410CD/ |title=Cappadonna - Eyrth, Wynd & Fyre - Audio CD [2CD&#93; - Underground Hip Hop - Store |publisher=Underground Hip Hop |date= |accessdate=2013-02-14}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n|''Hook Off''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hook-off-collectors-edition/id891699751|title=Hook Off (Collectors Edition) by Cappadonna on Apple Music|website=iTunes|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref>\n|June 17, 2014\n|\n|-\n|''The Pillage 2''\n|November 27, 2015\n|\n|-\n|''Ear Candy''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glfent.com/product-page/ear-candy|title=Ear Candy by Cappadonna on GLF Ent|website=www.glfent.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>\n|July 20, 2018\n|\n|}\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:350px;\"|Album Name\n! style=\"width:150px; text-align:center;\"|Release Date\n|-\n|''[[Ironman (Ghostface Killah album)|Ironman]]'' <small>([[Ghostface Killah]] album, billed alongside [[Raekwon]])</small>\n|1996\n|-\n|''Iron Fist Pillage'' (Soundtrack)\n|2001\n|-\n|''[[718 (album)|718]]'' <small>(with [[Theodore Unit]])</small>\n|2004\n|-\n|''Wu South Vl. 1'' (with Ratched Rush)\n|2005\n|-\n|''Wu South Vl. 2'' (with Ratched Rush)\n|2009\n|-\n|''The 2nd Coming'' <small>(with [[Bronze Nazareth]], [[Canibus]], M-Eighty, Nino Grave & [[Planet Asia]], as The Almighty)</small>\n|2013\n|}\n\n===Singles and EPs===\n\n* 1996 \"Taking Drastic Measures\"\n* 1996 ''Don't Be a Menace'' soundtrack - track \"Winter Warz\"\n* 1998 \"Slang Editorial\"\n* 1998 \"Run\"\n* 1999 \"Black Boy\"\n* 2001 \"Super Model\"\n* 2007 \"Don't Turn Around\"\n* 2009 \"Somebody's Got To Go\"\n* 2011 \"Cuban Link Kings\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070516045934/http://riotsound.com/hip-hop/rap/interviews/Cappadonna/index.php Cappadonna Interview]\n* [http://www.fakeshoredrive.blogspot.com/2007/12/fake-shore-drive-vs-cappadonna.html Cappadonna Interview with Fake Shore Drive]\n{{Cappadonna}}\n{{Wu-Tang Clan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan members]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York City]]\n[[Category:American beatboxers]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Staten Island]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "2601:46:200:27f7:7436:d9d8:3a39:4ab0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cappadonna"}
{"title_page": "Shyheim", "text_new": "{{short description|American rapper}}{{Redirect-distinguish|Manchild (album)|Man-Child}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name               = Shyheim\n| image              = Shyheim in 2011.jpg\n| image_size         =\n| caption            = Shyheim in 2011\n| birth_name         = Shyheim Dionel Franklin\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|11|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n|years_active = 1993 - present\n|label = {{hlist|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|[[EMI]]|[[Wu-Tang Records|Wu-Tang]]|[[Priority Records|Priority]]|[[ Nervous Records (US)|Nervous]]\n|associated_acts    = [[Wu-Tang Clan]], [[List of Wu-Tang Clan affiliates|Wu-Tang Killa Beez]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Shyheim Dionel Franklin''' (born November 14, 1979) is an American [[rapper]] and [[actor]] better known simply as '''Shyheim'''. He initially gained fame as a teenager, releasing his debut album [[AKA the Rugged Child]] at the age of 14 in 1994. He has spent the majority of his career affiliated with the [[Wu-Tang Clan]], frequently collaborating with [[Method Man]] and [[Ghostface Killah]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.10354/title.shyheim-talks-disrespectfully-speaking-bottom-up-records#|title=Shyheim Talks \"Disrespectfully Speaking,\" Bottom Up Records|first=HipHopDX -|last=Sryon|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager, Shyheim was considered one of hip hop's brightest prospects, being referred to as a \"[[wunderkind]]\"<ref name=\"theboombox.com\">{{cite web|url=http://theboombox.com/2pacs-hit-em-up-greatest-diss-song-of-all-time/|title=20 Years Later: Why 2Pac's 'Hit 'Em Up' Is the Greatest Diss Song of All Time|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> and a \"prodigy\",<ref name=\"auto\"/> even being admired by fellow rappers such as [[Jay-Z]], who said he \"looked up to him\" in admiration in his autobiography ''[[Decoded (memoir)|Decoded]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2012/11/in-case-youve-been-missing-shyheim/|title=In Case You\u2019ve Been Missing\u2026Shyheim  - XXL|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2010/11/10/shyheim-speaks-on-decoded-mention/|title=Shyheim Speaks On Decoded Mention|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> However, his career was later derailed due to legal problems.<ref name=\"silive.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silive.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/11/rapper_shyheim_franklin_is_sti.html|title=Rapper Shyheim Franklin is still in the game, despite his share of ups and downs|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nShyheim's [[Virgin Records]] debut, ''[[AKA the Rugged Child]]''. It included the [[hit single]] \"On and On\" the video of which featured [[Method Man]],<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and the album rose to #7 on the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|R&B]] [[record chart|chart]].\n\nShyheim joined others, notably [[The Fugees]], to provide a free concert to deaf children in a summer camp in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/21/nyregion/the-fresh-air-fund-meeting-urban-musicians-at-a-camp-in-the-country.html|title=The Fresh Air Fund;Meeting Urban Musicians At a Camp in the Country|date=July 21, 1996|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShyheim released another album in 1996, ''The Lost Generation'', which featured members of [[G.P. Wu]] and [[Brooklyn Zu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/172666-Shyheim|title=Shyheim|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> He also shared the stage with [[the Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Tupac Shakur]], and [[Big Daddy Kane]] at [[Madison Square Garden]], for a live freestyle session.<ref name=\"theboombox.com\"/><ref name=\"silive.com\"/> He also made an appearance on Big Daddy Kane's \"Show & Prove,\" which featured [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]], [[Sauce Money]], [[Scoob]] and [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/>\n\nShyheim resumed his career after almost a decade and released subsequent albums on the label he founded, Bottom Up Records.<ref name=\"auto\"/> His third and fourth albums, ''The Greatest Story Never Told'' and ''Enter the Bottom'', were released to little fanfare in 2004 and 2008. Shyheim released his fifth solo album, ''Disrespectfully Speaking'', October 2009 on his label Bottom Up Records.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Acting===\nShyheim starred in the [[music video|video]] for [[TLC (band)|TLC]]'s \"[[Waterfalls (TLC song)|Waterfalls]]\".<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/>\n\nHe has had roles in [[film]]s such as the 1996 [[Pam Grier]], [[Fred Williamson]], [[Jim Brown]], and [[Richard Roundtree]] vehicle ''[[Original Gangstas]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/11/movies/film-review-middle-aged-vigilantes-the-gang-has-grown-up.html|title=Middle-Aged Vigilantes: The Gang Has Grown Up|date=May 11, 1996|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/shyheim-franklin-58025428/|title=Shyheim Franklin - Biography and Filmography|first=Hollywood.com|last=Staff|date=May 23, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> ''[[In Too Deep (1999 film)|In Too Deep]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/1999/04/25/new-shyheim-album-due/|title=New Shyheim Album Due|first=Grouchy|last=Greg|date=April 25, 1999|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and ''[[The Preacher's Wife]]''<ref name=\"silive.com\"/><ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and he also starred in the television show ''[[The Parent Hood]]''.<ref name=\"silive.com\"/> Shyheim appeared in a small role in the prequel ''[[Carlito's Way: Rise to Power]]''.<ref name=\"silive.com\"/>\n\n==Legal problems==\nIn January 2014, Shyheim turned himself into authorities facing charges for leaving the scene of an accident during a hit-and-run accident that left one person dead.<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite web|last=Markman|first=Rob|date=January 9, 2014|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1720195/shyheim-faces-felony-charges/|title=Wu-Tang Affiliate Shyheim Faces Felony Charges In Fatal Hit And Run|work=MTV News|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On August 21, 2014, Shyheim was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he pled guilty to second degree manslaughter. He also received a concurrent term of seven years for a gun conviction, and is subject to five years' post release supervision. <ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Frank|date=August 21, 2014|url=http://www.silive.com/northshore/index.ssf/2014/08/rapper_shyheim_franklin_senten.html|title=Rapper Shyheim Franklin sentenced to up to 14 years in fatal hit-and-run|work=SILive.com|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Muhammad|first=Latifah|date=August 23, 2014|url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2014/08/23/shyheim-franklin-sentenced-to-up-to-14-years.html|title=Shyheim Franklin Sentenced to 14 Years for Hit-and-Run|work=BET.com|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On January 6, 2020, Shyheim was released from prison after serving a six year sentence. <ref>{{Cite web|last=Spezzamonte|first=Irene|date=January 8, 2020|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/01/wu-tang-affiliated-rapper-shyheim-franklin-out-on-parole-after-fatal-hit-and-run-conviction.html |title=Wu-Tang-affiliated rapper Shyheim Franklin out of prison after fatal hit-and-run conviction|work=SILive.com|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moorwood|first=Victoria|date=January 7, 2020|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/1/7/21055392/wu-tang-shyheim-released-from-prison|title=Wu-Tang Clan affiliate Shyheim released from prison: He served a five-year bid.|work=REVOLT.tv|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n*''[[AKA the Rugged Child]]'' (1994)\n*''[[The Lost Generation (album)|The Lost Generation]]'' (1996)\n*''Manchild'' (1999)\n*''The Greatest Story Never Told'' (2004)\n*''Disrespectfully Speaking'' (2009)\n\n==Filmography==\n*[[Original Gangstas]]\n*[[The Preacher's Wife]]\n*[[In Too Deep (1999 film)|In Too Deep]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/bottomupinfo Shyheims Official Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0291547}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan affiliates]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rapper}}{{Redirect-distinguish|Manchild (album)|Man-Child}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shyheim\n| image              = Shyheim in 2011.jpg\n| image_size         =\n| caption            = Shyheim in 2011\n| birth_name         = Shyheim Dionel Franklin\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1979|11|14}}\n| birth_place        = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alias              = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = [[Rapping|Rapper]]\n| years_active       = 1993\u20132014\n| children           = \n| relatives          = [[Ghostface Killah]] (cousin)<ref name=\"Lars\">{{cite web|author=Lars Brandle|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5862649/rapper-shyheim-franklin-arrested-after-new-years-day-hit-and-run|title=Rapper Shyheim Franklin Arrested After New Year's Day Hit-And-Run Death|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=2014-01-09|accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n| website            = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]|[[Hardcore hip hop]]\n}}\n| label = {{hlist|[[Virgin Records|Virgin]]|[[EMI]]|[[Wu-Tang Records|Wu-Tang]]|[[Priority Records|Priority]]|[[ Nervous Records (US)|Nervous]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = [[Wu-Tang Clan]]\n  }}<!--end-module-->\n}}\n\n'''Shyheim Dionel Franklin''' (born November 14, 1979) is an American [[rapper]] and [[actor]] better known simply as '''Shyheim'''. He initially gained fame as a teenager, releasing his debut album [[AKA the Rugged Child]] at the age of 14 in 1994. He has spent the majority of his career affiliated with the [[Wu-Tang Clan]], frequently collaborating with [[Method Man]] and [[Ghostface Killah]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.10354/title.shyheim-talks-disrespectfully-speaking-bottom-up-records#|title=Shyheim Talks \"Disrespectfully Speaking,\" Bottom Up Records|first=HipHopDX -|last=Sryon|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs a teenager, Shyheim was considered one of hip hop's brightest prospects, being referred to as a \"[[wunderkind]]\"<ref name=\"theboombox.com\">{{cite web|url=http://theboombox.com/2pacs-hit-em-up-greatest-diss-song-of-all-time/|title=20 Years Later: Why 2Pac's 'Hit 'Em Up' Is the Greatest Diss Song of All Time|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> and a \"prodigy\",<ref name=\"auto\"/> even being admired by fellow rappers such as [[Jay-Z]], who said he \"looked up to him\" in admiration in his autobiography ''[[Decoded (memoir)|Decoded]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2012/11/in-case-youve-been-missing-shyheim/|title=In Case You\u2019ve Been Missing\u2026Shyheim  - XXL|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2010/11/10/shyheim-speaks-on-decoded-mention/|title=Shyheim Speaks On Decoded Mention|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> However, his career was later derailed due to legal problems.<ref name=\"silive.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silive.com/entertainment/music/index.ssf/2009/11/rapper_shyheim_franklin_is_sti.html|title=Rapper Shyheim Franklin is still in the game, despite his share of ups and downs|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nShyheim's [[Virgin Records]] debut, ''[[AKA the Rugged Child]]''. It included the [[hit single]] \"On and On\" the video of which featured [[Method Man]],<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and the album rose to #7 on the US ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|R&B]] [[record chart|chart]].\n\nShyheim joined others, notably [[The Fugees]], to provide a free concert to deaf children in a summer camp in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/21/nyregion/the-fresh-air-fund-meeting-urban-musicians-at-a-camp-in-the-country.html|title=The Fresh Air Fund;Meeting Urban Musicians At a Camp in the Country|date=July 21, 1996|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShyheim released another album in 1996, ''The Lost Generation'', which featured members of [[G.P. Wu]] and [[Brooklyn Zu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/172666-Shyheim|title=Shyheim|publisher=|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> He also shared the stage with [[the Notorious B.I.G.]], [[Tupac Shakur]], and [[Big Daddy Kane]] at [[Madison Square Garden]], for a live freestyle session.<ref name=\"theboombox.com\"/><ref name=\"silive.com\"/> He also made an appearance on Big Daddy Kane's \"Show & Prove,\" which featured [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]], [[Sauce Money]], [[Scoob]] and [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/>\n\nShyheim resumed his career after almost a decade and released subsequent albums on the label he founded, Bottom Up Records.<ref name=\"auto\"/> His third and fourth albums, ''The Greatest Story Never Told'' and ''Enter the Bottom'', were released to little fanfare in 2004 and 2008. Shyheim released his fifth solo album, ''Disrespectfully Speaking'', October 2009 on his label Bottom Up Records.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Acting===\nShyheim starred in the [[music video|video]] for [[TLC (band)|TLC]]'s \"[[Waterfalls (TLC song)|Waterfalls]]\".<ref name=\"mtv.com\"/>\n\nHe has had roles in [[film]]s such as the 1996 [[Pam Grier]], [[Fred Williamson]], [[Jim Brown]], and [[Richard Roundtree]] vehicle ''[[Original Gangstas]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/05/11/movies/film-review-middle-aged-vigilantes-the-gang-has-grown-up.html|title=Middle-Aged Vigilantes: The Gang Has Grown Up|date=May 11, 1996|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=March 2017}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/shyheim-franklin-58025428/|title=Shyheim Franklin - Biography and Filmography|first=Hollywood.com|last=Staff|date=May 23, 2014|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> ''[[In Too Deep (1999 film)|In Too Deep]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://allhiphop.com/1999/04/25/new-shyheim-album-due/|title=New Shyheim Album Due|first=Grouchy|last=Greg|date=April 25, 1999|publisher=|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and ''[[The Preacher's Wife]]''<ref name=\"silive.com\"/><ref name=\"mtv.com\"/> and he also starred in the television show ''[[The Parent Hood]]''.<ref name=\"silive.com\"/> Shyheim appeared in a small role in the prequel ''[[Carlito's Way: Rise to Power]]''.<ref name=\"silive.com\"/>\n\n==Legal problems==\nIn January 2014, Shyheim turned himself into authorities facing charges for leaving the scene of an accident during a hit-and-run accident that left one person dead.<ref name=\"mtv.com\">{{cite web|last=Markman|first=Rob|date=January 9, 2014|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1720195/shyheim-faces-felony-charges/|title=Wu-Tang Affiliate Shyheim Faces Felony Charges In Fatal Hit And Run|work=MTV News|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On August 21, 2014, Shyheim was sentenced to 14 years in prison after he pled guilty to second degree manslaughter. He also received a concurrent term of seven years for a gun conviction, and is subject to five years' post release supervision. <ref>{{cite web|last=Donnelly|first=Frank|date=August 21, 2014|url=http://www.silive.com/northshore/index.ssf/2014/08/rapper_shyheim_franklin_senten.html|title=Rapper Shyheim Franklin sentenced to up to 14 years in fatal hit-and-run|work=SILive.com|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Muhammad|first=Latifah|date=August 23, 2014|url=http://www.bet.com/news/music/2014/08/23/shyheim-franklin-sentenced-to-up-to-14-years.html|title=Shyheim Franklin Sentenced to 14 Years for Hit-and-Run|work=BET.com|accessdate=March 9, 2015}}</ref> On January 6, 2020, Shyheim was released from prison after serving a six year sentence. <ref>{{Cite web|last=Spezzamonte|first=Irene|date=January 8, 2020|url=https://www.silive.com/news/2020/01/wu-tang-affiliated-rapper-shyheim-franklin-out-on-parole-after-fatal-hit-and-run-conviction.html |title=Wu-Tang-affiliated rapper Shyheim Franklin out of prison after fatal hit-and-run conviction|work=SILive.com|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moorwood|first=Victoria|date=January 7, 2020|url=https://www.revolt.tv/news/2020/1/7/21055392/wu-tang-shyheim-released-from-prison|title=Wu-Tang Clan affiliate Shyheim released from prison: He served a five-year bid.|work=REVOLT.tv|accessdate=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n*''[[AKA the Rugged Child]]'' (1994)\n*''[[The Lost Generation (album)|The Lost Generation]]'' (1996)\n*''Manchild'' (1999)\n*''The Greatest Story Never Told'' (2004)\n*''Disrespectfully Speaking'' (2009)\n\n==Filmography==\n*[[Original Gangstas]]\n*[[The Preacher's Wife]]\n*[[In Too Deep (1999 film)|In Too Deep]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/bottomupinfo Shyheims Official Website]\n* {{IMDb name|0291547}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:Virgin Records artists]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan affiliates]]\n[[Category:Gangsta rappers]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "2601:46:200:27f7:7436:d9d8:3a39:4ab0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shyheim"}
